\begin_layout Chapter
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
state discrimination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the most vital tools of quantum information theory is reading out
 the information.
 It is the probabilistic nature of quantum mechanics that one cannot simply
 obtain information encoded in states, the state is not an observable in
 quantum mechanics.
 When a quantum circuit or processor has acted on the input states to perform
 a task, the output needs to be read out.
 Thus after the processing occurs the task is to determine the state of
 the system.
 If the input states are orthogonal the process is trivial.
 Simply setting up detectors along the orthogonal directions and a click
 in those detectors will determine the state of the system.
 On the other hand discriminating among non orthogonal quantum states is
 not trivial.
 Since quantum mechanics does not allow for perfect discrimination of non
 orthogonal states the task becomes that of a measurement optimization problem.
 Not being able to perfectly discriminate quantum states is key to various
 quantum cryptographic schemes and quantum computing.
 The origin of the measurement optimization field dates back to the 70's
 by the works of Helstrom and Holevo.
 They minimized the average error rate of discriminating the input states.
 The field however gained momentum in the 90's as quantum information theory
 become very active primarily due to the factorization work of Peter Schor
 and quantum key distribution protocols such as B92.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Various optimum state discrimination measurement strategies have been developed
 with respect to some figure of merit.
 Two of those methods which we focus on are optimum Unambiguous Discrimination
 (UD) and Minimum Error (ME).
 In UD the observer is not allowed to make an error.
 Whenever he is handed a state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 he cannot conclude that he was given 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{j}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 We will show that this cannot be done with 100% success rate and that the
 observer must allow for inconclusive results and find an optimum measurement
 strategy which minimizes the average rate of inconclusive results.
 In the Minimum Error strategy the observer is not allowed to have inconclusive
 results.
 Thus errors are allowed and the task is to find optimum measurements that
 minimize the average error rate.
 ME and UD seem to be a special case of a more general scheme of optimum
 state discrimination measurement which can be approached by relaxing the
 conditions at either end.
 In the ME scheme the optimal error rate can be further reduced by allowing
 for some rate of inconclusive results.
 Thus the optimal average error rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E},$
\end_inset

 becomes a function of a given rate of allowed inconclusive results 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}(Q)$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, in UD, the optimal rate of the average inconclusive
 outcomes, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q,$
\end_inset

 may be reduced by allowing for some error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}$
\end_inset

.
 The failure rate becomes a function of a given error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(P_{E}).$
\end_inset

 The full analytical solution to this interpolation scheme with a Fixed
 Rate of Inconclusive Outcome, 
\begin_inset Formula $FRIO,$
\end_inset

 was first developed by Bagan 
\begin_inset Formula $et$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $al$
\end_inset

 [ref here].
 We provide a different approach to the 
\begin_inset Formula $FRIO$
\end_inset

 scheme using Neumark theorem.
 This approach has the advantage that it lends itself into an experimental
 realization which can be carried out using beam splitters and phase shifters.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
the following is directly from the paper
\end_layout

\end_inset

We have also extended this method to a different class of mixed states,
 states whose spectral form is such that the eigenvectors form a Jordan
 basis for the Hilbert space of the problem.
 The UD of such mixed states has been investigated and the optimal solution
 has been obtained in [21, 22].
 Thus, we know both the UD and the ME limit for these states.
 In this paper we will derive the optimal strategy with a Fixed Rate of
 Inconclusive Outcomes (
\begin_inset Formula $FRIO$
\end_inset

) that optimally interpolates between these two known limits.
 In particular, as the main finding of our paper, we will show that the
 optimal distribution of the fixed rate of inconclusive outcomes, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, among the 2-dimensional subspaces spanned by the pair of Jordan basis
 vectors is highly non-trivial and an interesting threshold-like structure
 emerges: As we start increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0$
\end_inset

 , first only one subspace receives the entire inconclusive rate.
 Then, as we increase 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 further, at a certain threshold a second subspace starts sharing the inconclusi
ve rate.
 If we increase 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 further, at another threshold a third subspace also starts sharing 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 , and so on, until above a last threshold all subspaces share the available
 inconclusive rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Cloning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we mentioned above, one of the reasons we need to develop optimum state
 discrimination measurement schemes is due to the no cloning theorem of
 Wootters, Zurek
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Wootters1982"

\end_inset

 and Dieks[].
 If one could copy non orthogonal quantum states then by making infinitely
 many copies, it would be possible to distinguish the states.
 Cloning machines which optimize some criteria with a limited degree of
 success have been developed.
 Those cloning machines fall under two categories: universal and state dependent.
 Universal cloning machines, which make copies of a completely unknown quantum
 state, were first developed first by Bŭzek and Hillery[].
 This scheme makes approximate copies of an unknown quantum state while
 optimizing the local fidelity, square overlap of the one of the approximate
 clones and the original state it is suppose to clone.
 The other category of cloning machine is state dependent.
 In this scheme the observer has full knowledge of the prepared states but
 does not know which is the state he is given.
 There are two subcategories within this scheme: approximate and exact cloning.
 Approximate state-dependent cloning machines deterministically generate
 approximate clones from a finite set of non-orthogonal quantum states while
 optimizing the local or global fidelity (the average square overlap between
 full set of approximate clones and the states to be cloned).
 Again Hillery and Buzek[] are the pioneers of this subcategory of cloning
 machines.
 In Exact state-dependent cloning machines, the other subcategory of quantum
 cloning machines, the task is to probabilistically make exact copies of
 the incoming non-orthogonal quantum states.
 This comes at the expense of allowing for failure results where the scheme
 fails to produce a copy altogether.
 Duan and Guo[] were first to develop probabilistic exact cloning machines
 for the two state input where the states are prepared with equal a-priori
 probabilities.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Our work..
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

We recently extended this method for the more general case where the a-priori
 probabilities of the incoming states are different.
 This extension not only solves the full problem but gives new insight into
 the nature of quantum cloning.
 The symmetry of the equal priors case completely solves the problem and
 no further optimization can be done.
 This symmetry however hides the true nature of the exact cloning machines
 which show up in the asymmetric case.
 This can be shown through the two step process: exact cloning then optimal
 UD.
 First procedure makes exact clones of the incoming two states.
 The exact clones are then sent to an optimal UD machine where the average
 failure rate is minimized.
 To combine the two step process the inconclusive rate from the cloning
 process is added to the inconclusive rate, weighed with the new a-priori
 probabilities, from the optimal UD.
 When the input states are prepared with equal a-priors the total amount
 of the inconclusive rate reaches the IDP limit.
 Hence cloning then performing optimal UD is equivalent to simply performing
 the optimal UD first, then prepare the clones.
 However this is not true for when the a-priors are different.
 After the two step process the total inconclusive rate is higher then the
 IDP limit.
 This suggests that during the cloning process some information is being
 leaked due to the asymmetry of the failure rate operators.
 When performing exact cloning, clones are produced but no measurement has
 been made, hence we do not know which states are being cloned.
 We simply know whether the procedure was successful or it failed.
 When it fails, the states are discarded.
 This is where the information leakage comes in.
 The state which is prepared most often shall have a higher rate of failure.
 This does not happen in the equal priors case because the failure rate
 are symmetric.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Implementation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Theoretically, the problem of Unambiguously discriminating between nonorthogonal
 but linearly independent quantum states has been solved when allowing for
 failure outcomes.
 The idea is to map the incoming nonorthogonal quantum states onto orthogonal
 states which can then be perfectly distinguished.
 This mapping is a non unitary transformation as the inner product is not
 preserved.
 These non unitary transformation can be performed with some probability
 of success by allowing for inconclusive outcomes.
 The task is to find an implementation scheme which minimizes the average
 probability of failure.
 Choosing a physical system to realize quantum information processes, which
 have otherwise been solved theoretically, is central challenge to building
 a quantum computer.
 Some of the systems in use today are: energy levels of ions, the orientation
 of nuclear spin, the presence or absence of a photon in a cavity [enter
 ref] and dual rail representation of a qubit[] 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
look up other what are the more recent systems
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will realize the implementation of our works of interpolation and ME
 using the dual rail representation of photons combined with a six-port,
 which is a linear device with three input and three output ports.
 The six-port can be realized with beamsplitters and phase shifters.
 First we will demonstrate the power and simplicity of this system by working
 out the implementation of UD by JA.
 Bergou 
\begin_inset Formula $et$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $al$
\end_inset

 [ ].
 Then from solving the ME and 
\begin_inset Formula $FRIO$
\end_inset

 via Neumark we show how that by choosing the dual rail representation of
 the photon combined with a six-port the implementation followes naturally.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Quantum State Discrimination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Unambiguous Discrimination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we give a review of the existing schemes of Unambiguous
 Discrimination (UD).
 Particularly that of two pure states as it is directly related with our
 work.
 When performing UD the detectors are not allowed to make an error.
 We first show that it is not possible to succeed at discriminating quantum
 states with 100% success rate.
 Another detector must be added which accounts for inconclusive results.
 The task is to minimize this rate of inconclusive results.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Two pure states via POVM
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An ensemble of quantum states is prepared with two possible pure states
 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 Each state is prepared with an a priori probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}=1.$
\end_inset

 The observer has full knowledge of the states and their priors.
 The preparer, Alice, picks up a state and hands it over to the observer,
 Bob.
 Bob's task it to determine which state he is given by performing a single
 measurement or a POVM on the individual system he is given.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The observer is not allowed to make an error when making a measurement.
 Let us assume Bob can indeed discriminate the given states with 100% success
 rate.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{2}$
\end_inset

 be detectors which cover the full Hilbert space spanned by the states 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{1}+\Pi_{2}=1
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the UD scheme the detector 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 detects only the state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and never clicks for 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{j}\rangle,$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}|\psi_{j}\rangle=0.$
\end_inset

 Multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $(1.1.1)$
\end_inset

 by 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 from the right and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\psi_{1}|$
\end_inset

 from the left we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\psi_{1}|\Pi_{1}|\psi_{1}\rangle=1$
\end_inset

 which is the probability of successfully identifying 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{|\psi_{1}\rangle, \ensuremath{p_{1}}}$
\end_inset

 .
 Similarly we get that we can also successfully identify 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 with a success rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}=\langle\psi_{2}|\Pi_{2}|\psi_{2}\rangle=1.$
\end_inset

 Seems like one can indeed discriminate two non-orthogonal quantum states
 with a 100% success rate.
 However multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $(1.1.1)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\psi_{1}|$
\end_inset

 from the left and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 from the right one gets 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle=0,$
\end_inset

 where we use the fact that 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}|\psi_{j}\rangle=0.$
\end_inset

 This means that the input states are orthogonal, but we started with nonorthogo
nal quantum states.
 Thus one cannot discriminate non-orthogonal quantum state with 100% success
 rate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can still perform Unambiguous Discrimination but with a modified scheme.
 We can modify 
\begin_inset Formula $(1.1.1)$
\end_inset

 by adding a third detector 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 which can click for both states 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle:$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{1}+\Pi_{2}+\Pi_{0}=1\label{eq:3povms}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The clicks from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 are all inconclusive, i.e we gain no information from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}.$
\end_inset

 Defining 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=\langle\psi_{1}|\Pi_{0}|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

and 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}=\langle\psi_{2}|\Pi_{0}|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 as the failure probabilities, we want to minimize the overall failure rate
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}$
\end_inset

 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now determine the POVM operators explicitly.
 First lets define the states to be in a plane, such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle=\cos\theta|0\rangle+\sin\theta|1\rangle$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle=\cos\theta|0\rangle-\sin\theta|1\rangle$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The detectors have to be orthogonal with the states for which they are not
 supposed to click, i.e 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}|\psi_{j}\rangle=0.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pi_{1}=c_{1}|\psi_{2}^{\perp}\rangle\langle\psi_{2}^{\perp}|,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pi_{2}=c_{2}|\psi_{1}^{\perp}\rangle\langle\psi_{1}^{\perp}|,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}^{\perp}\rangle=\sin\theta|0\rangle+\cos\theta|1\rangle$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}^{\perp}\rangle=-\sin\theta|0\rangle+\cos\theta|1\rangle$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 are yet to be determined based on the optimum strategies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the definition of success probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=\langle\psi_{i}|\Pi_{i}|\psi_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 we can replace the constants 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pi_{1}=\frac{p_{1}}{|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}^{\perp}\rangle|^{2}}|\psi_{2}^{\perp}\rangle\langle\psi_{2}^{\perp}|
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pi_{2}=\frac{p_{2}}{|\langle\psi_{2}|\psi_{1}^{\perp}\rangle|^{2}}|\psi_{1}^{\perp}\rangle\langle\psi_{1}^{\perp}|
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename projection.jpg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Projection
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To determine what the failure operator is, plug in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{2}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3povms"

\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{0}=I-\Pi_{1}-\Pi_{2}=I-\frac{p_{1}}{|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}^{\perp}\rangle|^{2}}|\psi_{2}^{\perp}\rangle\langle\psi_{2}^{\perp}|-\frac{p_{2}}{|\langle\psi_{2}|\psi_{1}^{\perp}\rangle|^{2}}|\psi_{1}^{\perp}\rangle\langle\psi_{1}^{\perp}|
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
after writing everything explicitly, the positivity constraint of the eigenvalue
s of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 gives the condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q_{1}q_{2}\geq|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{2},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where we used 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}=1-p_{i}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the above condition we can now optimize the failure rate
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Q & = & \eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
from the constraint we use the equality 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=s^{2}/q_{2},$
\end_inset

 plug this into 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 then optimize with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2},$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q=\frac{\eta_{1}s^{2}}{q_{2}}+\eta_{2}q_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\frac{\partial Q}{\partial q_{2}}=-\frac{\eta_{1}s^{2}}{q_{2}^{2}}+\eta_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=\sqrt{\frac{\eta_{2}}{\eta_{1}}}s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}=\sqrt{\frac{\eta_{1}}{\eta_{2}}}s,$
\end_inset

 plugging them back into Equation 
\begin_inset Formula $(2.1.4)$
\end_inset

 gives the optimal 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q=2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}s
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now check the conditions where this result holds.
 The individual error rates must be smaller or equal to one 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}\leq1.$
\end_inset

 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=\sqrt{\frac{1-\eta_{1}}{\eta_{1}}}s\leq1$
\end_inset

 gives the lower bound on the a-prior probabilities, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\geq\frac{s^{2}}{1+s^{2}}.$
\end_inset

 Similarly the condition that 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}\leq1$
\end_inset

 gives the upper bound on the a-priors 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\leq\frac{1}{1+s^{2}}.$
\end_inset

 Putting the two conditions together the POVM regime is valid in this range:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{s^{2}}{1+s^{2}}\leq\eta_{1}\leq\frac{1}{1+s^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Outside of this range it is interesting to see that the measurement strategy
 merges into the projective measurement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If one one the incoming states is prepared with a much higher probability
 say 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\gg\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

 we design an experiment where we have only two detection operators.
 One of them, 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{0}$
\end_inset

, the failure operator, simply projects into state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle,$
\end_inset

 the detector 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset

 projects onto the orthogonality of 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle,$
\end_inset

 thus it never clicks for 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle,$
\end_inset

 so that a click on 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset

 is associated with the state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 A click along 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{2}$
\end_inset

 is failure.
 The total failure rate is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{1}=\eta_{1}|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{2}+\eta_{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly for 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}\gg\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{2}=\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Putting the pieces together, the minimum value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 for the three different regimes can be written as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q=\begin{cases}
2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}s & \text{if }\frac{s^{2}}{1+s^{2}}\leq\eta_{1}\leq\frac{1}{1+s^{2}}\\
\eta_{1}|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{2}+\eta_{2}\text{ if } & \eta_{1}>\frac{1}{1+s^{2}}\\
\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{2}\text{ if } & \eta_{1}<\frac{s^{2}}{1+s^{2}}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is very interesting that the POVM gives the minimum 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 when it is valid.
 As soon as we step outside the boundaries it merges with the von Neumann
 projective measurement.
 Then the optimal failure is given by projecting the failure operator on
 the state which is least prepared.
 All of this arises very smoothly as can be seen by the graph.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Enter the graph showing the merge of POVM and projective.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename SSD.png

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Failure probability, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $vs.$
\end_inset

 the prior probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Two pure states via Neumark 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Theoretically the problem of minimizing the failure rate for two pure states
 has been solved in the above section.
 However to be able to implement those schemes we resort to Neumark's theorem
 which states that any POVM operator can be realized by generalized measurements.
 [fix it ] The system where the incoming states live are embedded in a larger
 Hilbert space called Ancilla.
 Then a Unitary operator entangles the degrees of freedom of the system
 with those of the Ancilla.
 Then projective measurements are performed in this larger system.
 These measurements will also transform the system states in the original
 Hilbert space because of the entanglement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To show the power of Neumark's theorem we will rederive the optimal failure
 rate of two nonorthogonal states.
 The incoming states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s},|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}\}$
\end_inset

 which live in the state Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 are embedded with the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|i\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 which live in the ancilla Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $A.$
\end_inset

 Now the system and the ancilla live in the larger Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H=S\varotimes A.$
\end_inset

 The incoming states in this larger Hilbert space can be written in the
 product form 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a},|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a}\}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a}=\sqrt{p_{1}}|\psi'_{1}\rangle_{s}|1\rangle_{a}+\sqrt{q_{1}}|\phi\rangle_{s}|0\rangle_{a}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a}=\sqrt{p_{2}}|\psi'_{2}\rangle_{s}|1\rangle_{a}+\sqrt{q_{2}}|\phi\rangle_{s}|0\rangle_{a}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of successfully discriminating the state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle_{s}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of failing to discriminate 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle_{s},$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}+q_{i}=1.$
\end_inset

 The unitary operator looks to take the two incoming states and make them
 orthogonal.
 When there is a click on the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|1\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 the input states have been separated and and output states 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi'_{i}\rangle_{s}$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal and thus fully distinguishable.
 If there is a click along the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 the incoming states have been collapsed into a single state which carries
 no information.
 That is why the choice on the setup of having the failed 
\begin_inset Formula $|\phi\rangle_{s}$
\end_inset

 state be the same, there should be absolutely no information left in the
 failed state, otherwise it is not optimal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve the problem we take the inner product of the two equations which
 gives the constraint.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s=\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is the overlap of the incoming states 
\begin_inset Formula $s\equiv\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 The quantity we want to minimize is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rest of the calculations are the same as in the POVM section and we
 do not need to repeat here.
 Implementation methods have been derived and we will show an example in
 the Implementation Chapter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Minimum Error
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Minimum Error (ME) strategy one is not allowed to abstain from identifyin
g an incoming state.
 Since it was shown that perfect discrimination is not possible then the
 detectors are allowed to err.
 A click in a detector can only identify a state with some probability of
 success and misidentify the state with some probability of error.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
POVM (Helstrom)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Discriminating two incoming mixed states by minimizing the error rate was
 first developed by Helstrom.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given an ensemble of two mixed states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{1},\rho_{2}\}$
\end_inset

 prepared with different a priori probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\eta_{1},\eta_{2}\}$
\end_inset

 the task is to minimize the rate for which the detectors misidentify a
 state.
 When the detector 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 clicks for state 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{j}$
\end_inset

 we consider that an error, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}=Tr(\rho_{i}\Pi_{j}).$
\end_inset

 Thus for two states we want to minimize the following expression.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\eta_{1}Tr(\rho_{1}\Pi_{2})+\eta_{2}Tr(\rho_{2}\Pi_{1})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}+\Pi_{2}=I$
\end_inset

 Equation 
\begin_inset Formula $2.2.2$
\end_inset

 can be rewritten as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{E}=\eta_{1}Tr(\rho_{1}(I-\Pi_{1}))+\eta_{2}Tr(\rho_{2}\Pi_{1})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{E} & = & \eta_{1}+Tr[(\eta_{2}\rho_{2}-\eta_{1}\rho_{1})\Pi_{1}]\\
 & = & \eta_{2}-Tr[(\eta_{2}\rho_{2}-\eta_{1}\rho_{1})\Pi_{2}]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda=\eta_{2}\rho_{2}-\eta_{1}\rho_{1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\eta_{1}+Tr(\Lambda\Pi_{1})=\eta_{2}-Tr(\Lambda\Pi_{2})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To minimize 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 should project onto the eigenvectors of the negative eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda,$
\end_inset

 on the other hand 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{2}$
\end_inset

 should project onto the positive eigenvectors.
 Let us write 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 into its spectral decomposition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Lambda=\eta_{2}\rho_{2}-\eta_{1}\rho_{1}=\sum_{i=1}^{d}\lambda_{i}|\lambda_{i}\rangle\langle\lambda_{i}|
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To implement the projection of the POVM operators onto the positive (or
 negative) eigenvectors the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 can be split into three categories without any loss of generality: negative,
 positive and zero:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\lambda_{i} & < & 0\text{ for }1\leq i<i_{o}\nonumber \\
\lambda_{i} & > & 0\text{ for \ensuremath{i_{o}\leq i<d}}\nonumber \\
\lambda_{i} & = & 0\text{ for \ensuremath{d\leq i<d_{s}} }
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then from the spectral decomposition we can rewrite 
\begin_inset Formula $(2.2.6)$
\end_inset

 in terms of the optimal POVM.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\eta_{1}+\sum_{i=1}^{i_{o}-1}\lambda_{i}\langle\lambda_{i}|\Pi_{1}|\lambda_{i}\rangle=\eta_{2}-\sum_{i=i_{o}}^{d_{s}}\lambda_{i}\langle\lambda_{i}|\Pi_{2}|\lambda_{i}\rangle
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}=\sum_{i=1}^{i_{o}-1}\lambda_{i}|\lambda_{i}\rangle\langle\lambda_{i}|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{2}=\sum_{i=i_{o}}^{d_{s}}\lambda_{i}|\lambda_{i}\rangle\langle\lambda_{i}|.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The POVMs need to satisfy the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\langle\lambda_{i}|\Pi_{j}|\lambda_{i}\rangle\leq1$
\end_inset

 which comes from the definition of the normalized probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}=Tr(\rho_{i}\Pi_{j}).$
\end_inset

 These POVMs are basically von Neuman projectors onto the corresponding
 eigenvectors.
 If we now replace the detection operators by the optimal detectors the
 minimum error can be expressed just in terms of the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{E} & = & \eta_{1}-\sum_{i=1}^{i_{o}-1}|\lambda_{i}|=\eta_{2}-\sum_{i=1}^{d_{s}}|\lambda_{i}|\nonumber \\
P_{E} & = & \frac{1}{2}[1-\sum_{i=1}^{d_{s}}|\lambda_{i}|]=\frac{1}{2}[1-Tr|\Lambda|]\nonumber \\
P_{E} & = & \frac{1}{2}[1-Tr|\eta_{2}\rho_{2}-\eta_{1}\rho_{1}|]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the states to be discriminated are pure, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,|\psi_{2}\rangle\},$
\end_inset

 the minimum error can be reduced to.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P=\frac{1}{2}[1-\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{2}}]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ME.png

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

Min Error
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Two pure states via Neumark 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just as we did in the UD case, we will solve the ME problem of discriminating
 two pure states via the Neumark setup because of it lends itself into an
 optical implementation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
explain the setup
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle|0\rangle & = & \sqrt{p_{1}}|\psi_{1}\rangle|1\rangle+\sqrt{r_{1}}|\psi_{2}\rangle|2\rangle,\\
U|\psi_{2}\rangle|0\rangle & = & \sqrt{r_{2}}|\psi_{1}\rangle|1\rangle+\sqrt{p_{2}}|\psi_{2}\rangle|2\rangle,
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the inner product gives the constraint
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s=\sqrt{p_{1}r_{2}}+\sqrt{p_{2}r_{1}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The quantity we are looking to minimize in the total error rate:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 subject to the above constraint.
 Setting up the Lagrangian and using 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}+r_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{E}=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}+\lambda[s-\sqrt{(1-r_{1})r_{2}}-\sqrt{(1-r_{2})r_{1}}]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Differentiating with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 the setting equal to zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial F_{E}}{\partial r_{1}}=\eta_{1}+\frac{1}{2}[\sqrt{\frac{r_{2}}{1-r_{1}}}-\sqrt{\frac{1-r_{2}}{r_{1}}}]=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial F_{E}}{\partial r_{2}}=\eta_{2}+\frac{1}{2}[-\sqrt{\frac{r_{1}}{1-r_{2}}}+\sqrt{\frac{1-r_{1}}{r_{2}}}]=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rearranging we get 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{2\eta_{1}}{\lambda}\sqrt{r_{1}(1-r_{1})}=\sqrt{r_{1}r_{2}}-\sqrt{(1-r_{1})(1-r_{2})}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{2\eta_{2}}{\lambda}\sqrt{r_{2}(1-r_{2})}=\sqrt{r_{1}r_{2}}-\sqrt{(1-r_{1})(1-r_{2})}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The left hand sides can be set to a constant, then we find the constant
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{2\eta_{i}}{\lambda}\sqrt{r_{i}(1-r_{i})}\equiv C
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r_{i} & = & \frac{1}{2}(1\pm\sqrt{1-\frac{\lambda^{2}c^{2}}{\eta_{i}^{2}}})=\frac{1}{2}(1-\sqrt{1-\frac{\delta^{2}}{\eta_{i}^{2}}})\\
r_{i} & = & \frac{1}{2}[1-A_{i}]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}=\sqrt{1-\frac{\delta^{2}}{\eta_{i}^{2}}}.$
\end_inset

 The smaller 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is picked as this represents error rate, which should be minimized.
 Now plug 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 into the constraint and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
s & = & \sqrt{(1-r_{1})r_{2}}+\sqrt{(1-r_{2})r_{1}}\\
2s & = & \sqrt{(1+A_{1})(1-A_{2})}+\sqrt{(1-A_{1})(1+A_{2})}\\
2s^{2} & = & 1-A_{1}A_{2}+\sqrt{(1-A_{1}^{2})(1-A_{2}^{2})}\\
2s^{2} & = & 1-A_{1}A_{2}+\frac{\delta^{2}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}\\
(2s^{2}-1 & -\frac{\delta^{2}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}})^{2}= & 1-\frac{\delta^{2}}{\eta_{1}^{2}}-\frac{\delta^{2}}{\eta_{2}^{2}}+\frac{\delta^{4}}{\eta_{1}^{2}\eta_{2}^{2}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After some tedious but trivial algebra:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta^{2}=\frac{4s^{2}(1-s^{2})\eta_{1}^{2}\eta_{2}^{2}}{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's plug this back into 
\begin_inset Formula $(2.2.23)$
\end_inset

 to get the explicit form of the individual error rates,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r_{1} & = & \frac{1}{2}[1-\frac{1-2\eta_{2}s^{2}}{\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}}]\\
r_{2} & = & \frac{1}{2}[1-\frac{1-2\eta_{1}s^{2}}{\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}}]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $2.2.16$
\end_inset

 we retrieve Helstrom bound 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{E} & = & \frac{1}{2}[1-\frac{\eta_{1}-2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}{\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}}-\frac{\eta_{2}-2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}{\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}}]\\
P_{E} & = & \frac{1}{2}[1-\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we mentioned above the advantage of solving the ME problem this way is
 that we now have explicit expression to individual error rates, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}.$
\end_inset

 In the Implementation chapter it is shown that the unitary operator can
 be written in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and then be decomposed into beam splitters and phase shifters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Optimal discrimination of a certain class of mixed states with a fixed rate
 of inconclusive outcome(FRIO)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Review of the FRIO solution for two pure states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Intro"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The two fundamental state discrimination strategies are the so-called minimum-er
ror (ME) strategy and the unambiguous discrimination (UD) strategy.
 In ME, every time a system is given and a measurement is performed on it
 a conclusion must be drawn about its state.
 Errors are permitted and in the optimal strategy the probability of making
 an error is minimized 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "helstrom"

\end_inset

.
 In UD, no errors are permitted at the expense of allowing an inconclusive
 measurement outcome to occur.
 When it occurs we don't learn anything about the state of the system and
 in the optimal strategy the probability of the inconclusive outcome is
 minimized 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ivanovic,dieks,peres,jaeger"

\end_inset

.
 It has been recognized that states can be discriminated unambiguously only
 if they are linearly independent 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "chefles1"

\end_inset

.
 Discrimination with maximum confidence (MC) can be applied to states that
 are not necessarily independent and for linearly independent states it
 reduces to unambiguous discrimination 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "croke,herzog1"

\end_inset

, so it can be regarded as a generalized UD strategy.
 In the MC strategy Bayes' rule is used to maximize the chance of the appropriat
e detector clicking for its desired state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is clear that UD (or MC for linearly dependent states) and ME are the
 two extremes of a more general strategy and one can approach this more
 general strategy from either end.
 Starting from UD one can allow a fixed inconclusive rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 to occur that is smaller than the optimal (minimal) inconclusive rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{C}$
\end_inset

 for UD, 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq Q\leq Q_{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Then one also needs to allow for errors to occur and one can minimize the
 error rate for the fixed value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 This scheme was introduced by Chefles and Barnett 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "chefles2"

\end_inset

 where they immediately provided the optimal solution for two pure states
 with equal prior probabilities, although at the time they did not prove
 full optimality of their solution.
 Later, Fiurášek and Ježek 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fiurasek"

\end_inset

 generalized this result for mixed states.
 Further useful bounds were obtained in Refs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "zhang,eldar"

\end_inset

, using the method of Semidefinite Programming (SDP).
 Alternatively, one can choose a certain fixed rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}$
\end_inset

 of errors to occur that is smaller than the optimal minimum error rate
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq P_{e}\leq P_{E}$
\end_inset

.
 Then one needs to allow for inconclusive outcomes to occur and one can
 minimize the inconclusive rate for a fixed value of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "touzel"

\end_inset

.
 The first approach yields the minimal error rate as a function of the given
 inconclusive rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}(Q)$
\end_inset

, while the second yields the minimum inconclusive rate as a function of
 the given error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(P_{e})$
\end_inset

.
 Since the two expressions result from optimizations under different conditions,
 it is not immediately obvious that they are, in fact, the same (in the
 sense of being inverses of each other).
 It is relatively straightforward to prove, however, that this must be true
 and the proof is based on showing that the opposite leads to contradiction
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "herzog2"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a recent burst of activity both approaches were solved analytically for
 two pure states and for other, highly symmetric situations.
 Actually, the second approach was solved earlier, first for two pure states
 with equal priors 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hayashi"

\end_inset

 and then for general occurrence probabilities 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sugimoto"

\end_inset

.
 However the connection with the first approach remained unnoticed in these
 two works.
 Quite recently, the first approach has been solved completely by two groups,
 using entirely different methods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bagan,Herzog1"

\end_inset

.
 Namely, Bagan 
\shape italic
et al.

\shape default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bagan"

\end_inset

 solved the problem introducing a transformation which formally eliminates
 the inconclusive part of the problem and reduces it to a ME problem with
 an extra optimization parameter.
 On the other hand, Herzog employed the SDP approach to obtain the solution
 for two pure states with arbitrary priors and for classes of special mixed
 states 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Herzog1"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal of this paper is to extend the method developed in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bagan"

\end_inset

 to a class of mixed states whose spectral form is such that the eigenvectors
 form a Jordan basis for the Hilbert space of the problem.
 The UD of such mixed states has been investigated and the optimal solution
 has been obtained in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HB,BFH"

\end_inset

.
 Later this was extended to programmable quantum state discriminators, where
 in a different context the ME of such mixed states has been solved 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BBFHH"

\end_inset

.
 Thus, we know both the UD and the ME limit for these states.
 In this paper we will derive the optimal strategy with a Fixed Rate of
 Inconclusive Outcomes (FRIO) that optimally interpolates between these
 two known limits.
 In particular, as the main finding of our paper, we will show that the
 optimal distribution of the fixed rate of inconclusive outcomes, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, among the 2-dimensional subspaces spanned by the pair of Jordan basis
 vectors is highly non-trivial and an interesting threshold-like structure
 emerges: As we start increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0$
\end_inset

, first only one subspace receives the entire inconclusive rate.
 Then, as we increase 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 further, at a certain threshold a second subspace starts sharing the inconclusi
ve rate.
 If we increase 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 further, at another threshold a third subspace also starts sharing 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, and so on, until above a last threshold all subspaces share the available
 inconclusive rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%The traditional measurement minimizes the chance of mistakenly identifying
 the state 
\backslash
cite{helstrom}.
 It is known as the minimum error (ME) strategy.
 In this strategy the measurements aim to identify the most prominent states,
 either pure 
\backslash
cite{Ban} or mixed 
\backslash
cite{Eldar,Chou}.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%For experimental purposes extending these strategies to include more classes
 of mixed states is necessary.
  Firstly, in the laboratory pure states are always accompanied by noise.
  Second, applications with multiple channels are necessary for extending
 the functionality of communications and computing protocols 
\backslash
cite{Kumar,Li,Bae,Zeilinger}.
  In this paper we generalize previous results by using an operator transformati
on to study the intermediate measurements in multiple subspaces.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The paper is organized as follows.
 In Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:2"

\end_inset

 we briefly review the FRIO solution for two pure states, viz.
 the transformation solution found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bagan"

\end_inset

, because the treatment presented in the body of the paper relies heavily
 on this method.
 In Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:3"

\end_inset

 we extend the FRIO problem to 2 subspaces, each two-dimensional.
 Then, in Sec.
 IV we consider a general Jordan Basis case, consisting of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 two-dimensional subspaces, where a Lagrangian optimization to minimize
 the error rate for fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 over all subspaces leads to the threshold structure.
 We illustrate the results on the example where the two mixed states to
 be discriminated are each of rank 3 and together they span a 6-dimensional
 Hilbert space.
 Because of the Jordan structure, the Hilbert space consists of three mutually
 orthogonal 2-dimensional Jordan subspaces.
 In Sec.
 V we deal with the projective regimes separately.
 Finally, in Sec.
 VI we conclude with a discussion.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Review of the FRIO solution for two pure states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first present a brief review of the method developed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bagan"

\end_inset

 for the two pure state optimal FRIO problem since the rest of the paper
 relies heavily on this method.
 We derive the maximum probability of success or, equivalently, the minimum
 probability of error in identifying the states, when a certain fixed rate
 of inconclusive outcomes is allowed.
 By varying the inconclusive rate, the scheme optimally interpolates between
 Unambiguous and Minimum Error discrimination (UD and ME), the two standard
 approaches to quantum state discrimination.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In all of these scenarios (UD, ME or FRIO) one is given a system which is
 promised to be prepared in one of two known pure states, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}=|\psi_{1}\rangle\langle\psi_{1}|$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{2}=|\psi_{2}\rangle\langle\psi_{2}|$
\end_inset

 , but we don't know which.
 The pure states are prepared with prior probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

, respectively, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 It is well known that two pure states can be discriminated both unambiguously
 and with minimum error.
 The optimal (minimal) inconclusive rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 for UD has been derived in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ivanovic,dieks,peres,jaeger"

\end_inset

, and is given by 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%Since two pure states can be unambiguously discriminated, the critical
 probability $Q_{
\backslash
rm c}$ coincides %with the optimal failure probability~$Q^{
\backslash
rm UD}$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{{\rm c}}=\left\{ \begin{array}{l}
\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}\cos^{2}\theta,\mbox{if \ensuremath{{\displaystyle \eta_{1}<\frac{\cos^{2}\theta}{1+\cos^{2}\theta}\equiv\eta_{1}^{(l)}}},}\\[0.7em]
\eta_{2}+\eta_{1}\cos^{2}\theta,\mbox{if \ensuremath{\eta_{1}>{\displaystyle \frac{1}{1+\cos^{2}\theta}\equiv\eta_{1}^{(r)}}},}\\[0.7em]
2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}\cos\theta\equiv Q_{0},\mbox{if \ensuremath{\eta_{1}^{(l)}\le\eta_{1}\le\eta_{1}^{(r)}}}\ ,
\end{array}\right.\label{Qmax}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|\equiv\cos\theta$
\end_inset

 is the overlap of the states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimal (minimal) error rate for ME has been derived in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "helstrom"

\end_inset

 and is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{{\rm E}}=\frac{1}{2}\left(1-\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}|\langle\psi_{1}\vert\psi_{2}\rangle|^{2}}\;\right).\label{PE}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For a compact derivation of these basic results see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bergourev"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the FRIO strategy we want three measurement outcomes, one that we identify
 with the first state, one that we identify with the second state and one
 that we do not identify with a state, corresponding to the inconclusive
 outcome.
 Therefore, we look for the solution as a three-element POVM (Positive Operator
 Valued Measure), 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{1}+\Pi_{2}+\Pi_{0}=I\ ,\label{POVM}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is the identity operator in the Hilbert space of the states.
 We identify a click in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{2}$
\end_inset

) with the first (second) state, while a click in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the inconclusive outcome.
 We wish to optimize (maximize) the success rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}=\eta_{1}tr[\Pi_{1}\rho_{1}]+\eta_{2}tr[\Pi_{2}\rho_{2}]$
\end_inset

 or, equivalently, minimize the error rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}=\eta_{1}tr[\Pi_{2}\rho_{1}]+\eta_{2}tr[\Pi_{1}\rho_{2}]$
\end_inset

, for a fixed failure rate, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q=tr[\Pi_{0}(\eta_{1}\rho_{1}+\eta_{2}\rho_{2})]\ .\label{Q}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Obviously, 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq Q\leq Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 and for 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 the FRIO strategy reduces to UD with 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}=0$
\end_inset

 while for 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0$
\end_inset

 the FRIO strategy reduces to ME with the error rate given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PE"

\end_inset

.
 For a given intermediate value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 the strategy minimizes 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method of solution is based on the observation that, for optimal FRIO,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 must be a rank one operator.
 Namely, if we assume the opposite, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a rank two operator then it maps the two input states into a pair of
 other two states that can be further discriminated, contradicting that
 the strategy is optimal.
 The starting point is to write 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}+\Pi_{2}=I-\Pi_{0}\equiv\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 Multiplying both sides of this equation by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Pi}_{1}+\tilde{\Pi}_{2}=I$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\Pi}_{i}=\Omega^{-1/2}\Pi_{i}\,\Omega^{-1/2}\ge0.\label{tildeops}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\tilde{\Pi}_{1},\tilde{\Pi}_{2}\}$
\end_inset

 is a POVM.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

 exists unless
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 has a unit eigenvalue, in which case we address the problem differently
 (see later).
 Defining the normalized transformed states 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\rho}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\emph on
a priori
\emph default
 probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\eta}_{i}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\rho}_{i}=\frac{\Omega^{1/2}\rho_{i}\Omega^{1/2}}{Tr(\Omega\rho_{i}))},\qquad\tilde{\eta}_{i}=\frac{\eta_{i}Tr(\Omega\rho_{i})}{1-Q},\label{tildestates}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

the error probability,
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}=(1-Q)\tilde{P}_{e}$
\end_inset

, becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\tilde{P}_{e} & = & Tr(\tilde{\eta}_{1}\tilde{\rho}_{1}\tilde{\Pi}_{2})+Tr(\tilde{\eta}_{2}\tilde{\rho}_{2}\tilde{\Pi}_{1}),\label{tildePe}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{P}_{s}=1-\tilde{P}_{e}$
\end_inset

.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "tildePe"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Pi}_{1}+\tilde{\Pi}_{2}=I$
\end_inset

 define a ME discrimination problem for the transformed states and 
\emph on
priors
\emph default
 given in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "tildestates"

\end_inset

.
 The optimal solution to this ME discrimination problem immediately follows
 by using the tilde quantities in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PE"

\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
begin{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
tilde{P}_{e}=
\backslash
frac{1}{2}
\backslash
left(1-
\backslash
sqrt{1-4
\backslash
tilde
\backslash
eta_1
\backslash
tilde
\backslash
eta_2|
\backslash
langle
\backslash
tilde
\backslash
psi_1|
\backslash
tilde
\backslash
psi_2
\backslash
rangle|^2}
\backslash
;%
\backslash
right).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
label{tildePe2}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
end{equation} 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $|\tilde{\psi}_{i}\rangle=\Omega^{1/2}|\psi_{i}\rangle/\sqrt{\langle\psi_{i}|\Omega|\psi_{i}\rangle}$
\end_inset

 being the properly normalized transformed states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the optimal
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a positive rank one operator it can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}=\xi|0\rangle\langle0|$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 is its eigenvalue, 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\xi\leq1$
\end_inset

, and the eigenstate belonging to 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle$
\end_inset

 and the orthogonal state is 
\begin_inset Formula $|1\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 In this basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=(1-\xi)|0\rangle\langle0|+|1\rangle\langle1|$
\end_inset

.
 Writing the input states also in this basis, 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle=c_{i}|0\rangle+s_{i}|1\rangle$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}\equiv\cos\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\equiv\sin\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

, and obtaining the transformed states and priors from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "tildestates"

\end_inset

, after some simplifications we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{P}_{e}^{{\rm ME}}=\frac{1}{2}\left\{ 1-\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}(\cos\theta-\xi c_{1}c_{2})^{2}/(1-Q)^{2}}\right\} ,\label{tildePe3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we used that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}\equiv\theta$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Q"

\end_inset

) that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\xi=\frac{Q}{\eta_{1}c_{1}^{2}+\eta_{2}c_{2}^{2}}.\label{xi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "tildePe3"

\end_inset

 depends only on one parameter, say
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}$
\end_inset

, which determines the orientation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 relative to that of the two pure states.
 The minimization over 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}$
\end_inset

 simplifies considerably, using Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "xi"

\end_inset

) and defining 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}\,\eta_{1}^{1/2}(\eta_{1}c_{1}^{2}+\eta_{2}c_{2}^{2})^{-1/2}\equiv\cos\varphi$
\end_inset

, and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}\,\eta_{2}^{1/2}(\eta_{1}c_{1}^{2}+\eta_{2}c_{2}^{2})^{-1/2}\equiv\sin\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 The resulting expression is minimum for
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\pi/4$
\end_inset

, yielding 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{e}^{{\rm min}}\!=\!\frac{1}{2}\!\left\{ 1-Q-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-\left(Q_{0}-Q\right)^{2}}\right\} \ ,\label{PeSol1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\leq Q_{0}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}$
\end_inset

 was introduced in the third line of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Qmax"

\end_inset

.
 This is the optimal error rate for an intermediate range of the prior probabili
ties.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%One can invert $P^{
\backslash
rm min}_e(Q)$ to obtain $Q$ and, in turn, $P^{
\backslash
rm max}_s$ as function of~$P_e$, %$P^{
\backslash
rm max}_s(P_e) = [P_e^{1/2}+(1-Q_0)^{1/2}]^2$, in agreement with~
\backslash
cite{hayashi}.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the validity of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PeSol1"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\le1$
\end_inset

 must hold.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%This condition determines the range of  %
\backslash
emph{priors} for which Eq.~
\backslash
eqref{PeSol1} is valid.
\end_layout

\end_inset

The definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\varphi$
\end_inset

 after Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "xi"

\end_inset

) give 
\begin_inset Formula ${\sqrt{\eta}_{2}c_{2}=\sqrt{\eta}_{1}c_{1}}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\pi/4$
\end_inset

 which, in turn, leads to 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}c_{1}^{2}=\eta_{2}c_{2}^{2}=\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\,{\sin^{2}\theta/(1-Q_{0})}$
\end_inset

, and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "xi"

\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=(1-Q_{0})Q/(2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\sin^{2}\theta)$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=1$
\end_inset

 defines the boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{b}$
\end_inset

, between the projective and POVM regimes, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{{\rm b}}\equiv{2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\sin^{2}\theta/(1-Q_{0})}.\label{Qb}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\xi\leq1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\leq Q_{{\rm b}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $Q>Q_{{\rm b}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Fig1"

\end_inset

 we plot 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm b}}$
\end_inset

 vs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 together for a fixed overlap, 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta=0.5$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\pi/3$
\end_inset

).
 The two curves intersect at 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{1}^{(l)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{1}^{(r)}$
\end_inset

, the same points as in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Qmax"

\end_inset

.
 The interval 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\eta_{1}\leq1$
\end_inset

 is thus divided into three regions.
 In regions
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

I and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

III, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm b}}<Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 and the solution
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PeSol1"

\end_inset

 is valid for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq Q<Q_{{\rm b}}$
\end_inset

 only.
 In Region II, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}^{(l)}\leq\eta_{1}\leq\eta_{1}^{(r)}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm c}}=Q_{0}<Q_{{\rm b}}$
\end_inset

 and the solution 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PeSol1"

\end_inset

 is valid for the entire 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq Q\leq Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 range.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 (dashed line, Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Qmax"

\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm b}}$
\end_inset

 (solid line, Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Qb"

\end_inset

) vs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\pi/3$
\end_inset

.
 Measurements can be optimized in the area under the dashed line, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Measurements in the area above 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{c}$
\end_inset

 are suboptimal.
 In the shaded areas between 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{b}$
\end_inset

 (regions I, left, and III, right) the optimal FRIO measurement is a projective
 measurement, in the unshaded area below 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{c}$
\end_inset

 (region II) the optimal measurement is a POVM.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the shaded parts of regions I and III one has 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm b}}\leq Q\leq Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 and, necessarily, 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=1$
\end_inset

.
 Hence,
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}=|0\rangle\langle0|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=|1\rangle\langle1|$
\end_inset

 are projectors.
 Therefore,
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

 does not exist in these areas and the case needs special consideration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The calculation of the error probability is most easily performed by realizing
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{2}$
\end_inset

 become degenerate, both must be proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{d}=|1\rangle\langle1|$
\end_inset

.
 The three-element POVM becomes a standard two element projective measurement,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\Pi_{d}=|1\rangle\langle1|,\ \Pi_{0}=|0\rangle\langle0|\}$
\end_inset

.
 We identify a click in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{d}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{2}$
\end_inset

) if 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\ge\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}\ge\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

), so 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e(s)}=\eta_{2}s_{2}^{2},\quad P_{s(e)}=\eta_{1}s_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=1-P_{e}-P_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 These equations completely determine the solution.
 There is nothing to optimize here, so we drop the superscript 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm min}$
\end_inset

 in what follows.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}=\theta$
\end_inset

 immediately gives 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(P_{e})$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q\!=\!1\!-\!P_{e}\!-\eta_{1(2)}\!\!\left(\!\sqrt{\!\frac{P_{e}}{\eta_{2(1)}}}\cos\theta\!\pm\!\sqrt{1\!-\!\frac{P_{e}}{\eta_{2(1)}}}\,\sin\theta\!\right)^{\!2}\!.\label{PeSol2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Inverting this equation gives 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}(Q)$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{e}=\eta_{2}\frac{2\eta_{1}\cos^{2}\theta(1-Q-Q_{2})-(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})(Q-Q_{2})-2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\sin\theta\cos\theta\sqrt{Q(1-Q)-\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\sin^{2}\theta}}{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\sin^{2}\theta}\ ,\label{PeSol2Exp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

but the resulting expression is not particularly insightful.
 However, we note that for 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}=0$
\end_inset

 (UD limit) one has
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{2}$
\end_inset

, given by the second line in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Qmax"

\end_inset

), and for 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{{\rm b}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}$
\end_inset

 reduces to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PeSol1"

\end_inset

, as it should.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Subspaces formalism: FRIO discrimination of two Rank 2 mixed states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:3"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this and the next section we consider the FRIO discrimination of two
 mixed states that exhibit a Jordan structure.
 The two states, with their respective 
\emph on
prior
\emph default
 probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

, are given in spectral (diagonal) form as, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\rho_{1} & = & \sum_{i=1}^{N}r_{i}\vert r_{i}\rangle\langle r_{i}\vert\nonumber \\
\rho_{2} & = & \sum_{i=1}^{N}s_{i}\vert s_{i}\rangle\langle s_{i}\vert\ .\label{rho1and2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle r_{i}\vert r_{j}\rangle=\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle s_{i}\vert s_{j}\rangle=\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 Each density matrix has rank 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and together they span a 
\begin_inset Formula $2N$
\end_inset

 dimensional Hilbert space.
 We assume that the Jordan condition, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle r_{i}\vert s_{j}\rangle=\delta_{ij}\cos\theta_{i}\ ,\label{jordan}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

holds so the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\vert r_{i}\rangle,\vert s_{i}\rangle\vert i=1,\ldots,N\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 forms a Jordan basis for the 
\begin_inset Formula $2N$
\end_inset

 dimensional Hilbert space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to the Jordan structure, instead of one 
\begin_inset Formula $2N$
\end_inset

 dimensional problem we have 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 mutually orthogonal 2-dimensional subspaces.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 subspace is spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert r_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert s_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 with 
\emph on
prior
\emph default
 probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}s_{i}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 The full discrimination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{2}$
\end_inset

 can be accomplished by performing the discrimination in each subspace independe
ntly of the others, i.e., by discriminating 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert r_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert s_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 in each subspace which is much simpler than the original problem.
 A physical implementation of this scheme is provided, e.g., by the transmission
 of two input states over several optical fibers.
 Each fiber contains two degrees of freedom, that could be two orthogonal
 polarizations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the present section we will focus on the 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2$
\end_inset

 case when we have to deal with two 2-dimensional subspaces only.
 We leave the general case of arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 to the next section.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%The two Rank 2 density matrices together span four dimensions and they
 are given as:
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
begin{eqnarray}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

% 
\backslash
rho_1 &=& r_1 
\backslash
vert r_1 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
langle r_1 
\backslash
vert  + r_2 
\backslash
vert r_2 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
langle r_2 
\backslash
vert 
\backslash
nonumber 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

% 
\backslash
rho_2 &=& s_1 
\backslash
vert s_1 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
langle s_1 
\backslash
vert  + s_2 
\backslash
vert s_2 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
langle s_2 
\backslash
vert 
\backslash
 .
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
end{eqnarray}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%These mixed states are shown in Fig.
 
\backslash
ref{Fig1}.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
begin{figure}[th]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%$%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
begin{array}{c}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
includegraphics[height=4 cm]{Figure1.png} 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
end{array}%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%$%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
caption{Visual representation of the input states in subspaces one and two.}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
label{Fig1}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
end{figure}
\end_layout

\end_inset

As discussed above, in this case we are dealing with two orthogonal 2-dimensiona
l subspaces.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 subspace is spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\vert r_{i}\rangle,\vert s_{i}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

 and our task is to perform the optimal FRIO discrimination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\vert r_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert s_{i}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 within subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The prior probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert r_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}r_{i}$
\end_inset

 while the prior probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert s_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}s_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We define their normalized probabilities as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\eta_{1,i} & \equiv & \frac{\eta_{1}r_{i}}{\eta_{1}r_{i}+\eta_{2}s_{i}},\nonumber \\
\eta_{2,i} & \equiv & \frac{\eta_{2}s_{i}}{\eta_{1}r_{i}+\eta_{2}s_{i}}\ ,\label{etaij}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1,i}+\eta_{2,i}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now introduce a fixed rate of inconclusive outcomes for subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq Q_{i}\leq Q_{c,i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{c,i}$
\end_inset

 is given by Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Qmax"

\end_inset

 with the obvious substitutions 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\rightarrow\eta_{1,i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}\rightarrow\eta_{2,i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\rightarrow\cos\theta_{i}=\langle r_{i}\vert s_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 We note that this reduces the problem to the FRIO discrimination of two
 pure states in subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, with prior probabilities given above.
 It follows immediately that the solution is given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PeSol1"

\end_inset

 in the POVM regime of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}\leq Q_{c,i},Q_{th,i}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PeSol2"

\end_inset

 in the projective regime of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{th,i}<Q_{i}\leq Q_{c,i}$
\end_inset

, again with the above substitutions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following we will focus mainly on the POVM regime where the solution
 in each subspace is given explicitly by Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PeSol1"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{e,i}=\frac{1}{2}(1-Q_{i}-\sqrt{(1-Q_{i})^{2}-(Q_{0,i}-Q_{i})^{2}})\ ,\label{Pei2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0,i}=2\sqrt{\eta_{1,i}\eta_{2,i}}\langle r_{i}|s_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}$
\end_inset

 was introduced in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Qmax"

\end_inset

 for the single subspace (two pure states) case, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0,i}$
\end_inset

 is its generalization for the case of two (or many) subspaces.
 We introduce the weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 of subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{1}r_{i}+\eta_{2}s_{i}=\omega_{i}\ ,\label{omegai}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where, obviously, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\omega_{1}+\omega_{2}=1\ .\label{weights}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then the total error rate can be written as a weighted sum of the error
 rates of the individual subspaces 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{e}=\omega_{1}P_{e,1}+\omega_{2}P_{e,2}\ .\label{Pe2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, the total inconclusive rate is a weighted sum of the inconclusive
 rates of the individual subspaces, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q=\omega_{1}Q_{1}+\omega_{2}Q_{2}\ .\label{Qtot2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We notice now that the total inconclusive rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is fixed, with the fixed value satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq Q\leq Q_{0}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{0}\equiv\omega_{1}Q_{0,1}+\omega_{2}Q_{0,2}\ ,\label{Q0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is the maximal inconclusive rate that the two subspaces can accommodate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The task is to determine the optimal distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 between the two subspaces, under the constraint that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Qtot2"

\end_inset

 is fixed.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%Since $Q$ on the l.h.s.
 can be written as $Q= 
\backslash
omega_{1} Q + 
\backslash
omega_{2} Q$ due to 
\backslash
eqref{weights}, one would naturally assume that $Q_{1} = Q_{2} = Q$ and
 each subspace contributes to the total inconclusive rate according to its
 weight.
  This, however, turns out not to be the case and the optimal distribution
 of the the total inconclusive rate between the two subspaces is far from
 being trivial.
 We can find the optimal $Q_{1}$ and $Q_{2}$ in the following way.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Qtot2"

\end_inset

 tells us that only one of the 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

s, say 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}$
\end_inset

, is an independent variable, since 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{2}=(Q-\omega_{1}Q_{1})/\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Inserting this into Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Pe2"

\end_inset

 it becomes a function of the independent variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 It can then be optimized with respect to this variable, yielding an optimal
 distribution of the fixed inconclusive outcomes between the two subspaces.
 Without loss of generality in what follows we assume the hierarchy 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{0,1}\geq Q_{0,2}\ .\label{hierarchy2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The optimization corresponds to finding the solution to 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial P_{e}/\partial Q_{1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 If we introduce the notation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{th}^{(1)}=0\ \ \ \ Q_{th}^{(2)}\equiv\frac{\omega_{1}(Q_{0,1}-Q_{0,2})}{1-Q_{0,2}}\ ,\label{Qth12}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

the result of this straightforward optimization can be written as 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
begin{widetext}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Q_{1}^{opt}=\left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
\frac{Q}{\omega_{1}} & \mbox{ if \ensuremath{Q_{th}^{(1)}\leq Q\leq Q_{th}^{(2)}}}\ ,\\
\frac{1-Q_{0,1}}{1-Q_{0}}(Q-Q_{th}^{(2)})+\frac{Q_{th}^{(2)}}{\omega_{1}} & \mbox{if \ensuremath{Q_{th}^{(2)}<Q\leq Q_{0}}}\ ,
\end{array}\right.\nonumber \\
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
end{widetext}
\end_layout

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Q_{2}^{opt}=\left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
0 & \mbox{ if \ensuremath{0\leq Q\leq Q_{th}^{(2)}}}\ ,\\
\frac{1-Q_{0,2}}{1-Q_{0}}(Q-Q_{th}^{(2)}) & \mbox{ if \ensuremath{Q_{th}^{(2)}<Q\leq Q_{0}}}\ .
\end{array}\right.\label{Q2opt}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
end{widetext}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Clearly, Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Qtot2"

\end_inset

 is satisfied by these solutions but there is no range where the naive expectati
on, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}=Q_{2}=Q$
\end_inset

, would hold.
 The subspace with the larger 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0,i}$
\end_inset

 which is the first subspace in our specific case, always accommodates a
 higher rate of inconclusive outcomes than the subspace with the lower 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0,i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most interesting aspect of the optimal solution is that a threshold
 structure emerges.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $Q<Q_{th}^{(2)}$
\end_inset

 the second subspace does not accommodate any inconclusive outcome at all
 and it operates at the Minimum Error level.
 In this region of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 all the inconclusive outcome is accommodated by the first subspace only.
 Above this threshold the two subspaces share the available inconclusive
 rate.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}Q_{0,1}>\omega_{2}Q_{0,2}$
\end_inset

, the first subspace always accommodates more inconclusive rate than the
 second, otherwise above some value of the total 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 the second subspace will accommodate more inconclusive rate than the first.
 The situation is depicted in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Fig2"

\end_inset

, for some specific values of the parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, inserting 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Q1opt"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Q2opt"

\end_inset

 into Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Pei2"

\end_inset

 and using the resulting expressions in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Pe2"

\end_inset

 yields the optimal error probability, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}$
\end_inset

, with a fixed rate of inconclusive outcomes, 
\begin_inset Formula $begin\{widetext\}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{E}=\left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
\frac{1}{2}\!\left\{ 1-Q-\sqrt{(\omega_{1}-Q)^{2}-\left(\omega_{1}Q_{0,1}-Q\right)^{2}}-\sqrt{(\omega_{2})^{2}-\left(\omega_{2}Q_{0,2}\right)^{2}}\right\}  & \mbox{ if \ensuremath{Q_{th}^{(1)}\leq Q\leq Q_{th}^{(2)}}}\ ,\\
\frac{1}{2}\!\left\{ 1-Q-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-\left(Q_{0}-Q\right)^{2}}\right\}  & \mbox{ if \ensuremath{Q_{th}^{(2)}<Q\leq Q_{0}}}\ ,
\end{array}\right.\label{PE2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
begin{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%P_{E} = 
\backslash
frac{1}{2}[1 - Q - 
\backslash
sum_{i=1}^{2} 
\backslash
omega_{i} 
\backslash
sqrt{ (1 - Q_{i}^{opt})^2 -(Q_{0,i} - Q_{i}^{opt} )^2} ] 
\backslash
 ,
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
label{PE2} 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{widetext}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 which is the main result of this section.
 It is valid in all regions of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, for the maximum allowable inconclusive rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\omega_{1}Q_{0,1}+\omega_{2}Q_{2,0}$
\end_inset

, Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PE2"

\end_inset

 reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=0$
\end_inset

, corresponding to optimal Unambiguous Discrimination of two subspaces 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HB,BFH"

\end_inset

, while for 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0$
\end_inset

 it reduces to the Minimum Error expression for two subspaces 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BBFHH"

\end_inset

, as it should.
 We close this section by displaying 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e,i}$
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

 in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Fig3"

\end_inset

, for some specific values of the parameters.
\end_layout

