\end_layout

\end_inset

 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,2,\ldots,N$
\end_inset

 and we introduced the notation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{th}^{(k)}=\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{k}\omega_{i}Q_{0,i}-Q_{0,k}\sum_{i=1}^{k}\omega_{i}}{1-Q_{0,k}}\ .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and also 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{th}^{(N+1)}=Q_{0}=Q_{max}$
\end_inset

, cf.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "NQ0"

\end_inset

.
 Obviously, for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,2$
\end_inset

 these results reproduce the results for two subspaces, Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Qth12"

\end_inset

--
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Q2opt"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inserting the optimal failure rates into the subspace-error rates 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e,i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "Pei2"

\end_inset

, gives the optimal error rates for the subspaces, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e,i}^{opt}$
\end_inset

.
 Then using these optimal subspace-error rates in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "NPe"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%Now the optimized subspace error rate is
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
begin{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%P_{e,i} = 
\backslash
frac{1}{2}( 
\backslash
omega_i-Q_i - (
\backslash
omega_i - Q_{0,i})
\backslash
sqrt{
\backslash
frac{1+ Q_0 -2 Q}{1-Q_0}}) 
\backslash
 ,
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset

gives the total optimal error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=\sum_{i=1}^{N}P_{e,i}^{opt}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
begin{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%P_e = 
\backslash
frac{1}{2}(1-Q-
\backslash
sqrt{(1-Q)^2-(Q-Q_0)^2}) 
\backslash
 .
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{widetext}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{E}=\left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
\frac{1}{2}\left[1-Q-\sqrt{\left(\sum_{i=1}^{k}\omega_{i}-Q\right)^{2}-\left(\sum_{i=1}^{k}\omega_{i}Q_{0,i}-Q\right)^{2}}-\sum_{i=k+1}^{N}\sqrt{(\omega_{i})^{2}-\left(\omega_{i}Q_{0,i}\right)^{2}}\right] & \mbox{ if \ensuremath{Q_{th}^{(k)}\leq Q\leq Q_{th}^{(k+1)}}}\\
{} & \mbox{ and \ensuremath{k<N}}\ ,\\
\frac{1}{2}\!\left[1-Q-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-\left(Q_{0}-Q\right)^{2}}\right] & \mbox{ if \ensuremath{Q_{th}^{(N)}<Q\leq Q_{0}}}\ ,
\end{array}\right.\nonumber \\
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
begin{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%P_{E} = 
\backslash
frac{1}{2}[1 - Q - 
\backslash
sum_{i=1}^{2} 
\backslash
omega_{i} 
\backslash
sqrt{ (1 - Q_{i}^{opt})^2 -(Q_{0,i} - Q_{i}^{opt} )^2} ] 
\backslash
 ,
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
label{PE2} 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{widetext}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 which is valid in all regions of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PEN"

\end_inset

 reduces to the two-subspaces solution, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PE2"

\end_inset

.
 For the maximum allowable inconclusive rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{0}$
\end_inset

, the second line in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PEN"

\end_inset

 holds and it reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=0$
\end_inset

, corresponding to optimal Unambiguous Discrimination of the subspaces 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HB,BFH"

\end_inset

, while for 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0$
\end_inset

 the first line holds and it reduces to the Minimum Error expression for
 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 subspaces 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BBFHH"

\end_inset

, as expected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%We remind ourselves that while this appears identical to the 2d solution
 (2.2), it in fact contains %parameters that are summed over all subspaces.
  This means that there is an onto relationship between N %dimensional and
 2d solutions that allows us to construct a variety of subspace strategies
 that replicate any %2d solution.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%ThresholdStructure%%%%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%  
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
subsection{Threshold Structure}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, the most interesting aspect of the optimal solution is that a structure
 with multiple thresholds emerges.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{th}^{(1)}=0\leq Q<Q_{th}^{(2)}$
\end_inset

 the total available inconclusive rate is accommodated by the first subspace
 only and all others operate at the Minimum Error level.
 According to the hierarchy introduced in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "hierarchy"

\end_inset

, the first subspace is the one with the largest 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0,i}$
\end_inset

.
 Then between 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{th}^{(2)}\leq Q<Q_{th}^{(3)}$
\end_inset

 the second subspace, the one with the second largest 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0,,i}$
\end_inset

 will also participate in sharing the available inconclusive rate, while
 the remaining 
\begin_inset Formula $N-2$
\end_inset

 subspaces continue to operate at the minimum error level.
 In general, in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{th}^{(k)}\leq Q<Q_{th}^{(k+1)}$
\end_inset

 the first 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 subspaces share the available inconclusive rate and the remaining 
\begin_inset Formula $N-k$
\end_inset

 subspaces remain at the minimum error level.
 Finally, in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{th}^{(N)}\leq Q\leq Q_{0}=Q_{max}$
\end_inset

 all 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 subspaces participate in sharing the available inconclusive rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easy to show that the expressions are continuous at the threshold,
 i.e.
 the expressions valid below the threshold and the ones valid above the
 threshold tend to the same values at the threshold, although their slopes
 are, in general, different below and above the threshold.
 Furthermore, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}Q_{0,i}>\omega_{i+1}Q_{0,i+1}$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 subspace always accommodates more inconclusive rate than the 
\begin_inset Formula $i+1^{st}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,\ldots,N$
\end_inset

, otherwise above some value of the total 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Formula $i+1^{st}$
\end_inset

 subspace will accommodate more inconclusive rate than the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 subspace, the 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}^{opt}(Q)$
\end_inset

 curves will intersect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We illustrate these results on the example of 
\begin_inset Formula $N=3$
\end_inset

.
 In Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Fig4"

\end_inset

, we plot the optimal failure rates 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}^{{\rm opt}}$
\end_inset

 and in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Fig5"

\end_inset

, we plot the optimal error rates 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e,i}^{{\rm opt}}$
\end_inset

 for the three subspaces as a function of the total failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 for some specific values of the parameters.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
