\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Quantum Cloning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
No-Cloning Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some of the schemes described above to discriminate quantum states would
 not be necessary if one could make copies of the non-orthogonal quantum
 states as can be done with classical states.
 If this were possible then the receiver, Bob, after receiving the state
 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 from the preparer, Alice, makes 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 number of copies.
 After a large set of copies the states become nearly orthogonal and almost
 fully distinguishable.
 The average inconclusive rate of failing to distinguish the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 copies of 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}=2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}s^{n}.$
\end_inset

 For a large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 the inconclusive rate is very small and Bob can discriminate nearly all
 incoming states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus while in classical information it is possible to make exact copies
 of information, as this dissertation is printed on this paper, multiple
 times by a printer.
 The no-cloning theorem restricts the receiver for doing the same with quantum
 states.
 More specifically it is non-orthogonal quantum states which cannot be copied,
 as classical states are a special case of quantum states, that of orthogonal
 states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now show a proof by contradiction of why such a quantum cloning machine
 cannot exist.
 Suppose there is such a cloning machines with an input and an output port.
 Inside the machine there are two slots: 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 slot for the system state,
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle,$
\end_inset

 to be copied, and an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 slot for the ancilla space where the input state is to be copied.
 Let the ancilla space be in some blank space 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle,$
\end_inset

 then the initial state of the copying machine would be: 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle|0\rangle.$
\end_inset

 A unitary operator would copy the state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle:$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U|\psi_{i}\rangle|0\rangle=|\psi_{i}\rangle|\psi_{i}\rangle
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let there be two possible input states to be copied, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,|\psi_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 and we are interested in a quantum cloning machine which produces 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 is sent and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 is sent.
 The unitary operator would do the following.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle|0\rangle & = & |\psi_{1}\rangle|\psi_{1}\rangle\\
U|\psi_{2}\rangle|0\rangle & = & |\psi_{2}\rangle|\psi_{2}\rangle
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inner product of these equations gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\psi_{2}|\psi_{1}\rangle\langle0|0\rangle=|\langle\psi_{2}|\psi_{1}\rangle|^{2}\Rightarrow s=s^{2}.$
\end_inset

 This condition can be satisfied only if 
\begin_inset Formula $s=0$
\end_inset

, states are orthogonal, or 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1,$
\end_inset

 the two states are the same.
 But we said that the two states are distinct and non-orthogonal.
 Thus one cannot design a unitary device which makes perfect clones of an
 unknown quantum system deterministically.
 Here we only proved that non-orthogonal pure states cannot be copied through
 a unitary process.
 Other proofs exist which show that this holds for mixed states and also
 for other non-unitary processes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since such a machine cannot be designed the next logical step is how to
 build a quantum machine which produces clones similar to the input states
 while allowing for some fidelity or inconclusive results.
 We derive some previous results considering such quantum cloning machines
 and also provide new results for optimal exact cloning with some inconclusive
 rate allowed.
 In a follow up paper we interpolate between the deterministic cloning scheme
 and exact cloning by relaxing some of the conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Exact cloning with failure rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we are concerned with making exact copies of the given quantum state.
 It is indeed possible to make exact copies but only probabilistically.
 This is very similar to the Unambiguous Discrimination where one discriminates
 between a given set of non orthogonal quantum states unambiguously while
 allowing for a failure rate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We approach probabilistic cloning via the Neumark formulation.
 The system is embedded in a larger Hilbert space where the extra degrees
 of freedom are customarily called the ancilla.
 Then a unitary transformation entangles the system degrees of freedom with
 those of the ancilla.
 The input states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}^{M}\rangle_{s},|\psi_{2}^{M}\rangle_{s}\}$
\end_inset

 which live in the state Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 are embedded with the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|i\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 which live in the Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $A.$
\end_inset

 Now the system and the ancilla live in the larger Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H=S\varotimes A.$
\end_inset

 The incoming states in this larger Hilbert space can be written in the
 product form 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}^{N}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a},|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a}\}.$
\end_inset

 The unitary should do the following: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}^{M}\rangle|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p_{1}}|\psi_{1}^{N}\rangle|\alpha_{1}\rangle+\sqrt{q_{1}}|\Phi_{1}\rangle\ket 0,\label{eq:clone1}\\
U|\psi_{2}^{M}\rangle|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p_{2}}|\Psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|\alpha_{2}\rangle+\sqrt{q_{2}}|\Phi_{2}\rangle\ket 0,\label{eq:clone2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the rate of having successfully produced a perfect clone, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the rate of having failed to do so.
 The inner product of each of the above equation with its own transpose
 gives the normalized probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}+q_{i}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 are the input states we wish to clone and their corresponding ancillas
 are 
\begin_inset Formula $|\alpha_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Getting a click in 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle$
\end_inset

 means we have failed to clone and discard the state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the inner product of the transpose of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:clone1"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:clone2"

\end_inset

 we get the constraint of success and failure rate in terms of the overlap
 of the input states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s^{M}=\sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}s^{N}\alpha+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\phi
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle,\quad s'=\langle\Psi_{1}|\Psi_{2}\rangle,\quad\alpha=\langle\alpha_{1}|\alpha_{2}\rangle,\quad\phi=\langle\Phi_{1}|\Phi_{2}\rangle
\]

\end_inset

In the above setup the ancilla corresponding to successfully making a clone
 is distinct.
 The failed states are also distinct.
 That is the most general case.
 In order for the success rates to be optimal we take the ancilla to be
 the same.
 Looking at the constraint we absorb 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, meaning there is more copies which would come at the expense of a lower
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 .
 More explicitly this can be shown for the equal priors case shown below.
 We will now show the the failed states should also be the same.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Phi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Phi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 are different that means that there is still information left in the failed
 states and we can still perform an Unambiguous State discrimination and
 probabilistically determine whether we received 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 .
 The optimal strategy is one which leaves no information at all in the failed
 states and the overlap 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\langle\Phi_{2}|\Phi_{1}\rangle=1.$
\end_inset

 Any click from the failed state is simply discarded as failure.
 The revised Neumark setup reduces to: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}^{M}\rangle|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p_{1}}|\psi_{1}^{N}\rangle\ket{\alpha}+\sqrt{q_{1}}|\Phi\rangle\ket 0,\\
U|\psi_{2}^{M}\rangle|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p_{2}}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|\alpha\rangle+\sqrt{q_{2}}|\Phi\rangle\ket 0,
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The constraint simplifies into:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s^{M}=\sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}s^{N}+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}.\label{eq:clone overlap}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the constraint on the parameters to optimize the average failure
 rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equal a-priori.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the input states are prepared with equal a-priori probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{2}=\frac{1}{2},$
\end_inset

 the problem is quite trivial.
 It was first solved by Duan and Guo
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Duan1998"

\end_inset

.
 For equal priors the success and failure rate reduce to: 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=p_{2}=p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=q_{2}=q$
\end_inset

.
 The constraint 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:clone overlap"

\end_inset

 reduces into:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s^{M}=ps^{N}+q,
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
using the unitarity condition 
\begin_inset Formula $p+q=1,$
\end_inset

 the problem can be fully solved:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
s^{M} & = & ps^{N}+(1-p),\nonumber \\
p & = & \frac{1-s^{M}}{1-s^{N}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the failure rate is 
\begin_inset Formula $q=1-p=\frac{s^{M}-s^{N}}{1-s^{N}}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the optimization of the probabilistic exact cloning is fully solved
 from the constrained derived from the Neumark setup and no further optimiation
 is needed.
 In the limit of producing infinetily many clones, 
\begin_inset Formula $N\rightarrow inf,$
\end_inset

 the failure rate becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $q=s^{M},$
\end_inset

 which is the IDP limit in unambiguous state discrimination.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
General Case I
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now seek to solve the general problem for when the incoming states are
 prepared with different a priori probabilities.
 In this section we show a geometric/numeric solution using the Lagrange
 multipliers method with the constraint given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:clone overlap"

\end_inset

.
 We want to optimize the average rate of failing to produce a copy , 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s=\sqrt{(1-q_{1})(1-q_{2})}s^{2}+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}],\label{eq:1 to 2 cloning constraint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where we set 
\begin_inset Formula $M=1,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2.$
\end_inset

 The function to be maximized is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{S}=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}+\lambda[s-\sqrt{(1-q_{1})(1-q_{2})}s^{2}-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}],
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the Lagrange multiplier to be determined which optimizes 
\begin_inset Formula $Q.$
\end_inset

 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial F/\partial q_{i}=0$
\end_inset

, solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{2\eta_{1}}{\lambda} & = & \sqrt{\frac{q_{2}}{q_{1}}}-\sqrt{\frac{1-q_{2}}{1-q_{1}}}s^{2}\label{eq:lagr1}\\
\frac{2\eta_{2}}{\lambda} & = & \sqrt{\frac{q_{1}}{q_{2}}}-\sqrt{\frac{1-q_{1}}{1-q_{2}}}s^{2}\label{eq:lagr2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\equiv\sqrt{\frac{q_{2}(1-q_{1})}{q_{1}(1-q_{2})}},$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\sqrt{\frac{q_{1}}{q_{2}}} & = & \frac{\lambda}{2\eta_{1}}[1-\frac{s^{2}}{A}]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\sqrt{\frac{q_{2}}{q_{1}}} & = & \frac{\lambda}{2\eta_{2}}[1-As^{2}]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiplying the above two equations, setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=\frac{4\eta\eta_{2}}{\lambda^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\frac{s^{4}-\delta+1}{s^{2}}$
\end_inset

 results into a quadratic equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\delta-1 & = & s^{2}[s^{2}-A-\frac{1}{A}]\nonumber \\
0 & = & A^{2}-CA+1\label{eq:1st quadratic in A}\\
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This quadratic equations is one of the equations we will use to obtain the
 value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another quadratic equation emerges using the two equations in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagr1"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagr2"

\end_inset

.
 First let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\equiv\frac{\lambda}{2\eta_{1}}[1-\frac{s^{2}}{A}]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\alpha}=\frac{\lambda}{2\eta_{2}}[1-As^{2}]$
\end_inset

 the relationship between the two failure rates becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sqrt{q_{1}}=\alpha\sqrt{q_{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
using this and the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed explicilety in terms of the fixed constants: 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\eta_{1},\eta_{2},s\}$
\end_inset

 and the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 which is yet to be determined.
 The derivation starts from the definition at 
\begin_inset Formula $A,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{2}=\frac{q_{2}(1-q_{1})}{q_{1}(1-q_{2})}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{q_{1}}{1-q_{1}}A^{2}=\frac{q_{2}}{1-q_{2}}$
\end_inset

 replace 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=\alpha^{2}q_{2}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\alpha^{2}q_{2}}{1-\alpha^{2}q_{2}}A^{2}=\frac{q_{2}}{1-q_{2}}$
\end_inset

 solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2},$
\end_inset

 then using the relationship 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=\alpha^{2}q_{2}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
q_{2} & = & \frac{1-\alpha^{2}A^{2}}{\alpha^{2}(1-A^{2})}\\
q_{1} & = & \frac{1-\alpha^{2}A^{2}}{(1-A^{2})}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the expression of the individual failure rates which are yet to
 be optimized subject to the constraint.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

 is replaced in the constrained given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1 to 2 cloning constraint"

\end_inset

 and from there the optimal value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 can be obtained.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some prior calculations before replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 into the constraint will simplify the overall algebra:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $1-q_{1}=\frac{A^{2}(\alpha^{2}-1)}{(1-A^{2})}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $1-q_{2}=\frac{\alpha^{2}-1}{\alpha^{2}(1-A^{2})}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we are ready to replace 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1-q_{i}$
\end_inset

 into the constraint:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
s & = & \frac{A(\alpha^{2}-1)}{\alpha(1-A^{2})}s^{2}+\frac{1-\alpha^{2}A^{2}}{\alpha(1-A^{2})}\\
(1-A^{2})s & = & \frac{1}{\alpha}(1-s^{2}A^{2})-\alpha A^{2}(1-\frac{s^{2}}{A})\\
(1-A^{2})s & = & \frac{\lambda}{2\eta_{2}}(1-s^{2}A^{2})^{2}-\frac{\lambda A^{2}}{2\eta_{1}}(1-\frac{s^{2}}{A})^{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where we replaced 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{ \alpha=\frac{\lambda}{2\eta_{1}}[1-\frac{s^{2}}{A}]\text{ and }\frac{1}{\alpha}=\frac{\lambda}{2\eta_{2}}[1-As^{2}] }.$
\end_inset

 After some trivial algebra another quadratic equation and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 emerges:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A^{2}-\frac{2s^{2}(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})}{\eta_{1}s^{4}-\eta_{2}+2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s/\lambda}A+\frac{\eta_{1}-\eta_{2}s^{4}+2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s/\lambda}{\eta_{1}s^{4}-\eta_{2}+2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s/\lambda}=0\label{eq: 2nd quadratic in A}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The combination of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1st quadratic in A"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: 2nd quadratic in A"

\end_inset

 should give the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 which in turn gives explicit solution to the minimum individual failure
 rates, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i},$
\end_inset

 and overall optimal failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}.$
\end_inset

 Analytically such a solution is hard to achieve as one would have to solve
 a sixth order quadratic equation.
 Simply by plotting the two quadratic equations as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 the solution can be obtained at the intersection of the two graphs.
 There will be multiple intersections, hence multiple values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda.$
\end_inset

 The one which gives the lowest value of the overall failure rate is chosen.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/ashehu/Desktop/intersect(A1, A2).jpg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Enter some graphs from mathematica for some specific values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\eta_{1},\eta_{2},s\}$
\end_inset

 where the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 can be read off
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our future work we would like to obtain a closed form solution of 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}.$
\end_inset

 One approach would be by making some educated guesses for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
General case II 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(will probably not use this version)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We try a different approach here derived by Emili Bagan.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us start by parametrizing the constraint: 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $s^{M}=\sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}s^{N}+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{p_{i}}=\cos\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{q_{i}}=\sin\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\theta_{i}\leq\pi/2$
\end_inset

 the constraint becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
s^{M} & = & \cos\theta_{1}\cos\theta_{2}s^{N}+\sin\theta_{1}\sin\theta_{2}\\
s^{M} & = & \frac{1}{2}[\cos(\theta_{1}+\theta_{2})+\cos(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})]s^{N}-\frac{1}{2}[\cos(\theta_{1}+\theta_{2})-\cos(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})]\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\equiv\cos(\theta_{1}+\theta_{2}),y\equiv\cos(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
s^{M} & = & \frac{1}{2}[(x+y)s^{N}-(x-y)]\\
s^{M} & = & \frac{1}{2}[-(1-s^{N})x+(1+s^{N})y]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $-1\leq x\leq1,-1\leq y\leq1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As this is the equation of a straight line we can write this in parametric
 form.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x=\frac{1\text{-}(1+s^{N})t}{s^{N-M}},y=\frac{1\text{-}(1-s^{N})t}{s^{N-M}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1-s^{N-M}}{1-s^{N}}\leq t\leq\frac{1}{1-s^{N}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1-s^{N-M}}{1-s^{N}}\leq t\leq\frac{1+s^{N+M}}{1-s^{N}}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1-s^{N-M}}{1-s^{N}}\leq t\leq min\{\frac{1}{1-s^{N}},\frac{1+s^{N+M}}{1-s^{N}}\}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now express the success and failure probabilities in terms of the
 new parametrization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{p_{1}}=\cos{\frac{1}{2}\arccos\frac{1\text{-}(1+s^{N})t}{s^{N-M}}+\frac{1}{2}\arccos\frac{1\text{-}(1-s^{N})t}{s^{N-M}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{p_{2}}=\cos{\frac{1}{2}\arccos\frac{1\text{-}(1+s^{N})t}{s^{N-M}}-\frac{1}{2}\arccos\frac{1\text{-}(1-s^{N})t}{s^{N-M}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{q_{1}}=\cos{\frac{1}{2}\arcsin\frac{1\text{-}(1+s^{N})t}{s^{N-M}}+\frac{1}{2}\arcsin\frac{1\text{-}(1-s^{N})t}{s^{N-M}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{q_{2}}=\cos{\frac{1}{2}\arcsin\frac{1\text{-}(1+s^{N})t}{s^{N-M}}-\frac{1}{2}\arcsin\frac{1\text{-}(1-s^{N})t}{s^{N-M}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The range of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 changes into 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1-s^{N-M}}{1-s^{N}}\leq t\leq1$
\end_inset

 as the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 need to be positive.
 For example 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{p_{1}}=\cos{\frac{1}{2}\arccos(-s^{M})+\frac{1}{2}\arccos(s^{M})}=1$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{M}\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{q_{1}}=\cos{\frac{1}{2}\arcsin(-s^{M})+\frac{1}{2}\arcsin(s^{M})}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Enter some graphs here for specific values.
 m=1, n=2, s=.., 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we are looking to minimize the average failure rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
the minimum of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}q'_{1}+\eta_{2}q'_{2}=0$
\end_inset

 and we can express the priors in the new parametrization form 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\frac{q'_{2}}{q'_{2}-q'_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}=\frac{q'_{1}}{q'_{1}-q'_{2}}.$
\end_inset

 Since the problem is symmetric in 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\Leftrightarrow\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

 we can analyze the problem for 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\leq1/2.$
\end_inset

 For the extreme point of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=0$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $q'_{2}=0\Rightarrow\frac{d}{dt}\sqrt{q_{2}}=0$
\end_inset

 and we can obtain the maximum value of 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{dt}\sqrt{q_{2}}=\frac{\sqrt{p_{2}}}{2s^{N-M}}(\frac{1+s^{N}}{\sqrt{1-x^{2}}}-\frac{1-s^{N}}{\sqrt{1-y^{2}}})=0\Rightarrow t_{max}=\frac{1-s^{2(N-M)}}{1-s^{2N}}$
\end_inset

 thus 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{min}=\frac{s^{2M}-s^{2N}}{1-s^{2N}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{max}=\frac{s^{M}-s^{N}}{1-s^{N}}$
\end_inset

which is true for 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Exact Cloning then Unambiguous Discrimination.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is interesting to see the connection between quantum cloning and state
 discrimination.
 We consider the two step process where we first clone then make a measurement.
 The other way around, state discrimination first then cloning is less interesti
ng because once we have succeed in discriminating a state we can make as
 many copies as we wish by simply preparing them with the knowledge we get
 from the discrimination step.
 On the other hand making a clone then performing state discrimination gives
 some interesting results.
 For the case when the incoming states are prepared with equal priors we
 show that cloning first then performing UD on the cloned states which come
 with some new a priori probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

 reaches the IDP limit.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea of the two step process is the following: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Given an ensemble of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 quantum states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,|\psi_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 make 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 exact clones while allowing for a rate of inconclusive outcomes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Then perform optimal unambiguous discrimination on the successfully cloned
 states throwing away the failed states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Equal priors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Exact Cloning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We showed that for equal priors and a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 copies of two non-orthogonal states we could successfully make exact copies
 with a probability 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{clone}=\frac{1-s^{M}}{1-s^{N}}.$
\end_inset

 The average failure rate, failing to clone a state is 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{clone}=1-P_{clone}=\frac{s^{M}-s^{N}}{1-s^{N}}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Unambiguous Discrimination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After the input states are sent through the deterministic exact cloning
 machines, 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 states of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,|\psi_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 come out through the output port.
 The cloning machine only makes copies and does not say which state it has
 made a copy of.
 The clones are now sent through an unambiguous discriminating machine to
 distinguish the incoming states, each comes with a probability 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $P_{clone}=\frac{1-s^{M}}{1-s^{N}}.$
\end_inset

 The standard Neumark theorem is used to discriminate the incoming clones:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle^{\oplus N}\ket 0 & = & \sqrt{p}|\phi\rangle|1\rangle+\sqrt{q}|\Phi\rangle|0\rangle\\
U|\psi_{1}\rangle^{\oplus N}\ket 0 & = & \sqrt{p}|\phi^{\perp}\rangle|2\rangle+\sqrt{q}|\Phi\rangle|0\rangle\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inner product gives 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{N}=q.$
\end_inset

 We have to take into consideration the fact that the states come in with
 a priori probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}p=\frac{1}{2}\frac{1-s^{M}}{1-s^{N}}$
\end_inset

, the average inconclusive rate for discriminating the incoming pair of
 states is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\tilde{\eta}_{1}q_{1}+\tilde{\eta}_{2}q_{2}=\eta_{1}p_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}p_{2}q_{2}=\frac{1-s^{M}}{1-s^{N}}s^{N}$
\end_inset

 ,where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{2}=\frac{1}{2},q_{1}=q_{2}=s^{N}$
\end_inset

 and success rate is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=p_{2}=\frac{s^{M}-s^{N}}{1-s^{N}}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total inconclusive rate for the two step process: cloning failure rate
 plus unambiguous discrimination failure rate:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Q_{total} & = & Q_{clone}+Q_{UD}\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{s^{M}-s^{N}}{1-s^{N}}+\frac{1-s^{M}}{1-s^{N}}s^{N}=s^{M}\label{eq:overlap}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After this two step process the IDP limit is reached for UD of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 non-orthogonal states .
 In equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:overlap"

\end_inset

 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Deterministic State Dependent Quantum Cloning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we re-derive the works of Chefles and Barnett in designing
 an approximate quantum cloning machine for two possible input states while
 maximizing the global fidelity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 non orthogonal quantum states with 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 copies each 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle^{\otimes M}=|\psi_{1}\rangle|\psi_{2}\rangle...|\psi_{M}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 The states are unknown and our task is to produce 
\begin_inset Formula $N>M$
\end_inset

 copies, as best as we can.
 Introducing an ancilla state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\chi\rangle$
\end_inset

 which is 
\begin_inset Formula $N-M$
\end_inset

 dimensional the goal is to transform the state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{j}\rangle|\chi\rangle$
\end_inset

 into the state which approximates the N exact copies of the input state
 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{j}^{N}\rangle.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is deterministic cloning, although imperfect, clones are generated
 on demand.
 The authors choose the global fidelity rate to improve the quality of the
 clones so they resemble the given copies as best as possible.
 This measure was introduced by Brub et al [enter citation].
 Thus given a set 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 of non orthogonal states 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle^{\otimes M},$
\end_inset

 we wish to produce a set 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 clones 
\begin_inset Formula $|\phi_{j}\rangle^{\otimes N}$
\end_inset

 while optimizing the global fidelity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{MN}=\sum_{j=1}^{K}\eta_{j}|\langle\psi_{j}^{N}|\phi_{j}\rangle|^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other figures of merit can also be used to improve the quality of the clones,
 such as local fidelity.
 The local fidelity is the average fidelity of each of the individual clones
 of each of the N subsystems measured against the input states 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{j}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 The authors choose the global fidelity due to its close connection to state
 discrimination.
 We are also very interested in the connection between cloning and state
 discrimination, particularly in the two step process where clones are first
 produced then they are unambiguously discriminated.
 We discover some very interesting features which are described in another
 section.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The global fidelity can be expressed differently if unitary operator acts
 on the input states 
\begin_inset Formula $U|\psi_{j}^{M}\rangle|\chi\rangle=|\phi_{j}^{N}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{MN}=\sum_{j=1}^{K}\eta_{j}|\langle\psi_{j}^{N}|U|\psi_{j}^{M}\rangle|\chi\rangle|^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maximizing the fidelity can be explicitly solved for an M set of two possible
 input states, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,|\psi_{2}\rangle\}.$
\end_inset

 It was originally solved by Brub 
\begin_inset Formula $et$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $al$
\end_inset

 for the case when the the incoming states are prepared with equal a priori
 probabilities.They noticed that the optimum clones 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\Phi_{1}\rangle,|\Phi_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 lie in the subspace spanned by the input states to be cloned 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,|\psi_{2}\rangle\}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A unitary produces 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 copies 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Phi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Phi_{2}\rangle,$
\end_inset

 to resemble the original states as best as possible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}^{M}\rangle|i\rangle & = & |\Phi_{1}^{N}\rangle\\
U|\psi_{2}^{M}\rangle|i\rangle & = & |\Phi_{2}^{N}\rangle
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inner product of the above two equations gives a relationship between
 the input and the output states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{M} & = & |\langle\Phi_{1}|\Phi_{2}\rangle|^{N}\\
s^{M} & = & t^{N}\label{eq:3.4.6}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{M=}|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{M},$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{N}=|\langle\Phi_{1}|\Phi_{2}\rangle|$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The input states can be expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
|\psi_{1}^{N}\rangle & = & \cos\theta|1\rangle+\sin\theta|0\rangle\\
|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle & = & \cos\theta|1\rangle-\sin\theta|0\rangle
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
similarly the clones yet to be optimized can be expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
|\phi_{1}\rangle & = & \cos\phi_{1}|1\rangle+\sin\phi_{1}|0\rangle\\
|\phi_{2}\rangle & = & \cos\phi_{2}|1\rangle-\sin\phi_{2}|0\rangle
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using this general representation of input and output states and using the
 overlap relation in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3.4.6"

\end_inset

 we see that the sum of the output angles is fixed as 
\begin_inset Formula $|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{M}=\cos^{M}2\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\langle\phi_{1}|\phi_{2}\rangle|^{N}=\cos^{N}(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2})\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos^{M}2\theta=\cos^{N}(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}).$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The global fidelity in terms of the angles becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{MN} & = & \eta_{1}|\langle\psi_{1}|\phi_{1}\rangle|^{2}+\eta_{2}|\langle\psi_{2}|\phi_{2}\rangle|^{2}\\
 & = & \eta_{1}(\cos\theta\cos\phi_{1}+\sin\theta\sin\phi_{1})+\eta_{2}(\cos\theta\cos\phi_{2}+\sin\theta\sin\phi_{2})\\
 & = & \eta_{1}\cos^{2}(\theta-\phi_{1})+\eta_{2}\cos^{2}(\theta-\phi_{2})
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rewriting the fidelity in terms of the sum and difference of the output
 angles, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F_{MN} & = & \eta_{1}\cos^{2}(\theta-\frac{\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}}{2}-\frac{\phi_{1}-\phi_{2}}{2})+\eta_{2}\cos^{2}(\theta-\frac{\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}}{2}+\frac{\phi_{1}-\phi_{2}}{2})\\
 & = & \eta_{1}\cos^{2}(\alpha-x)+\eta_{2}\cos^{2}(\alpha+x)\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}[\eta_{1}(\cos2(\alpha-x)+1]+\frac{1}{2}[\eta_{2}(\cos2(\alpha+x)+1]\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}[1+\eta_{1}(\cos2(\alpha-x)+\eta_{2}(\cos2(\alpha+x)]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\theta-\frac{\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}}{2}$
\end_inset

 is fixed and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\frac{\phi_{1}-\phi_{2}}{2}$
\end_inset

 is the only variable to optimize with.
 Differentiating with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\eta_{1}\sin(\alpha-x) & = & \eta_{2}\sin(\alpha-x)\\
\eta_{1}[\sin2\alpha\cos2x-\cos2\alpha\cos2x] & = & \eta_{2}[\sin2\alpha\cos2x+\cos2\alpha\cos2x]\\
(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})\sin2\alpha\cos2x & = & \cos2\alpha\cos2x\\
(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})\tan2\alpha & = & \tan2x\label{eq:tan2x}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
This is the relationship that gives the optimal clones and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 should be replaced in 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{MN}$
\end_inset

.
 To be able to use this relationship we re-express 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{MN}$
\end_inset

 in a different way: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}[1+\eta_{1}(\cos2(\alpha-x)+\eta_{2}(\cos2(\alpha+x)]\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}[\cos2\alpha\cos2x\{1+(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})\tan2\alpha\tan2x\}]+\frac{1}{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 we can rewrite 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:tan2x"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})\tan2\alpha=\frac{\sin2x}{\cos2x}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $....\cos2x=\frac{\sqrt{1-\cos^{2}2x}}{(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})\tan2\alpha}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})^{2}\tan^{2}(2\alpha)}},$
\end_inset

 finally the optimal fidelity can be expressed in terms of the a-priori
 probabilities and the overlap of the input states only .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}[1+\cos2\alpha\cos2x\{1+(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})\tan2\alpha\tan2x\}]\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}[1+\frac{\cos2\alpha}{\sqrt{1+(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})^{2}\tan^{2}(2\alpha)}}\{1+(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})^{2}\tan^{2}2\alpha]\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}[1+\cos2\alpha\sqrt{1+(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})^{2}\tan^{2}2\alpha)}]\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}[1+\sqrt{\cos^{2}2\alpha+(1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2})\sin^{2}2\alpha)}]\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}[1+\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\sin^{2}2\alpha}]\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}[1+\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\sin^{2}(2\theta-(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}))}]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos^{M}2\theta=\cos^{N}(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2})$
\end_inset

 in the limit of producing infinite copies 
\begin_inset Formula $N\rightarrow infinity$
\end_inset

 fidelity merges into the helstrom bound in discriminating of two pure states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{M∞}=\frac{1}{2}[1+\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\cos^{2}(2\theta)}]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is one of the connections between cloning and state discrimination,
 it emerges in the infinite number of clones being produced.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hybrid Cloning:Interpolation between exact and approximate cloning 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equal priors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution to the interpolation of cloning for equal a priori probabilities
 has been derived by Chefles et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chefles1999"

\end_inset

.
 The authors develop a scheme which depending on how exact requiring clones
 to be can interpolate between exact cloning with inconclusive results in
 one extreme and optimal approximate cloning on the other extreme.
 In our work this scheme has been generalized for the case when the input
 states are prepared with different a priori probabilities.
 First we show the derivation of the equal priors as it will help to better
 understand the general case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{2}=1/2,$
\end_inset

 the output states are symmetric, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}=\phi_{2}=\phi,$
\end_inset

 and the optimal global fidelity, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{MN}$
\end_inset

, derived in section() reduces to 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}[1+\sqrt{1-\sin^{2}(2\theta-2\phi)}]\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}[1+\cos^{2}(2\theta-2\phi)]\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Duan and Guo 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Duan1998"

\end_inset

 showed that the maximum success probability of obtaining 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 exact clones from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 given copies of non orthogonal quantum states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,|\psi_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 which are prepared with equal a priori probabilities is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{MN}=\frac{1-s^{M}}{1-s^{N}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is the overlap of the input states 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 The success rate for one to two cloning, 
\begin_inset Formula $M=1,N=2,$
\end_inset

 reduces into:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{12}=\frac{1}{1+s}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The interpolation takes us from optimal exact cloning to maximum fidelity.
 Given a set 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of two non-orthogonal quantum states, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,|\psi_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 the goal is to make 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 clones 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\phi_{1}\rangle,|\phi_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

, which are similar to the input states but not perfect.
 The Neumark setup is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle^{\otimes M}|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p}|\phi_{1}\rangle^{\oplus N}|1\rangle+\sqrt{q}|f\rangle|0\rangle\label{eq:NeumarkClone1}\\
U|\psi_{2}\rangle^{\oplus M}|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p}|\phi_{2}\rangle^{\oplus N}|1\rangle+\sqrt{q}|f\rangle|0\rangle\label{eq:NeumarkClone2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The input states are prepared with equal a priori probabilities.
 A click in the 
\begin_inset Formula $|1\rangle$
\end_inset

 direction means that we succeed in making the clones and the probability
 of success is 
\begin_inset Formula $p.$
\end_inset

 A click in the 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle$
\end_inset

 direction means that we failed to create a clone with a probability 
\begin_inset Formula $q.$
\end_inset

 The inner product or 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NeumarkClone1"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NeumarkClone2"

\end_inset

 gives the constraint: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s^{M}=pt^{N}+q
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the unitarity condition 
\begin_inset Formula $p+q=1,$
\end_inset

 the average rate of successfully making a clone is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p=\frac{1-s^{M}}{1-t^{N}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is the overlap of the clones 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\langle\phi_{1}|\phi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 If the final states are orthogonal, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 then the state separation reaches the IDP limit and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{S}=P_{IDP}=1-|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{M}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we express the overlap of the output states in terms on the success
 rates and the overlap of input states,
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos2\theta=|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{N}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
|\langle\phi_{1}|\phi_{2}\rangle|^{N} & = & 1-\frac{1-|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{M}}{P_{S}}\\
\cos^{N}(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}) & = & 1-\frac{P_{IDP}}{P_{S}}\label{eq:seperation}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where the exact clones live in an N dimensional space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1,2}^{N}\rangle=\cos\theta|1\rangle\pm\sin\theta|0\rangle$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The approximate clones can be expressed as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $|\phi_{1,2}\rangle=\cos\phi_{1}|1\rangle\pm\sin\phi_{1}|0\rangle$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fidelity rate for equal priors is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{MN}=\frac{1}{2}[1+\cos(2\theta-(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2})]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and we want to use the relationship in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:seperation"

\end_inset

.
 Let us expand the cosine term 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(2\theta-(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2})=\cos2\theta\cos(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2})+\sin2\theta\sin(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fidelity becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\\
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}[1+|\langle\psi_{1}^{N}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|(1-\frac{P_{IDP}}{P_{S}})+\frac{1}{P_{S}}((1-|\langle\psi_{1}^{N}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|^{2})(P_{S}^{2}-(P_{S}-P_{IDP})^{2})^{1/2})]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 As 
\begin_inset Formula $N\rightarrow\inf,|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{N}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{MN}$
\end_inset

 reduces to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{MN}=\frac{1}{2}[1+\frac{1}{P_{S}}\sqrt{P_{S}^{2}-(P_{S}-P_{IDP})^{2}}].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also express the fidelity in terms of fixed failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=1-P_{S}$
\end_inset

 which serves as the parameter by which we are interpolating and the optimal
 failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}=|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}[1+|\langle\psi_{1}^{N}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|(1-\frac{1-Q_{o}}{1-Q})+\frac{1}{1-Q}((1-|\langle\psi_{1}^{N}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|^{2})((1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2})^{1/2})]\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2(1-Q)}[(1-Q)+Q_{o}^{N}(Q_{o}-Q)+\sqrt{(1-Q_{o}^{2N})[(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}]}]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $N\rightarrow\inf,|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{N}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}[1+\frac{1}{1-Q}\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}].\\
(1-Q)F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)+\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(1-Q)F_{MN}=P_{succes}$
\end_inset

, the probability of successfully identifying a state.
 (This is a different success rate then the 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{S}$
\end_inset

 defined above, the 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{S}$
\end_inset

 was defined as the rate of successfully carrying out a state separation.
 )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{success} & = & \frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)+\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This formula describes the relationship between the discrimination of states
 with a fixed rate of inconclusive outcome.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0$
\end_inset

 it reaches the Helstrom bound of minimum error, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{o}$
\end_inset

 reaches the IDP limit in UD.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
State Separation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equal Priors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
General State separation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We approach state separation via the Neumark formulation.
 The system is embedded in a larger Hilbert space where the extra degrees
 of freedom are customarily called the ancilla.
 Then a unitary transformation entangles the system degrees of freedom with
 those of the ancilla.
 The input states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s},|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}\}$
\end_inset

 which live in the state Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 are embedded with the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|i\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 which live in the Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $A.$
\end_inset

 Now the system and the ancilla live in the larger Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H=S\varotimes A.$
\end_inset

 The incoming states in this larger Hilbert space can be written in the
 product form 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a},|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a}\}.$
\end_inset

 The unitary should do the following: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p_{1}}|\phi_{1}\rangle|\alpha\rangle+\sqrt{q_{1}}|\Phi_{o}\rangle|f\rangle,\label{eq:separation1}\\
U|\psi_{2}\rangle|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p_{2}}|\phi_{2}\rangle|\alpha\rangle+\sqrt{q_{2}}|\Phi_{o}\rangle|f\rangle,\label{eq:separation2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
were 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket f$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal.
 A projective measurement along the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 means that the states have succesfully become more distinguishable with
 a success rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

, otherwise a measurement in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket f$
\end_inset

 space means that the process has failed to produce more distinguishable
 states and the states are discarded with a probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inner product of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:separation1"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:separation2"

\end_inset

 gives the unitarity constraint:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s=\sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}s'+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $s=|\braket{\psi_{1}}{\psi_{2}}|^{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s'=|\braket{\phi_{1}}{\phi_{2}}|^{N}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For given 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

 and average failure probability 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, we wish to find out the minimum value of the final overlap 
\begin_inset Formula $s'$
\end_inset

 as a function of the initial overlap 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 The same difficulties encountered in perfect probabilistic cloning show
 up here and we will proceed along the same lines, giving the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $(s,\min s')$
\end_inset

 in parametric form, rather than attempting to give 
\begin_inset Formula $\min s'$
\end_inset

 as a explicit function of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, which would require solving a high degree polynomial equation.
 We choose a change of variables which linearizes the unitarity constrait
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:constraint"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{1}p_{1}=t^{2},\quad q_{1}q_{2}=z^{2}.\label{eb cha qs -> z & t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The condition becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z=s-s't,\qquad0\le t,z\le1,\qquad0\le s'\le s.
\]

\end_inset

It is a straight line in the (first quadrant of the) plane 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

-
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 with (negative) slope
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $-s'$
\end_inset

 and crossing the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-axis at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=s$
\end_inset

.
 From the first Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eb cha qs -> z & t"

\end_inset

) we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t^{2}=(1-q_{1})(1-q_{2})=1+z^{2}-q_{1}-q_{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

 and substituting back in the second Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eb cha qs -> z & t"

\end_inset

) we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{1}(q_{1}-1+t^{2}-z^{2})+z^{2}=0.
\]

\end_inset

We now solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

 and obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{1}=\frac{1+z^{2}-t^{2}\pm\sqrt{(1+z^{2}-t^{2})^{2}-4z^{2}}}{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Similarly, for 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

 we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{2}=\frac{1+z^{2}-t^{2}\mp\sqrt{(1+z^{2}-t^{2})^{2}-4z^{2}}}{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Therefore, the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}$
\end_inset

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2Q=1+z^{2}-t^{2}\pm(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})\sqrt{(1+z^{2}-t^{2})^{2}-4z^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

We now solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 After a bit of algebra we obtain 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


