{\displaystyle \frac{Q}{2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}},\quad} & {\rm if} & \quad0\le Q\le2\eta_{1}\\[2em]
{\displaystyle \sqrt{\frac{Q-\eta_{1}}{\eta_{2}}},\quad} & {\rm if} & \quad2\eta_{1}<Q\le1.
\end{array}\right.
\]

\end_inset

There is a second point that we need to define.
 We first note that for equal priors the curve is simply the hyperbola 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z^{2}=t^{2}+2Q-1,
\]

\end_inset

which intersects the straight line 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z=1-t
\]

\end_inset

at the point 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(z,t)=(Q,1-Q).
\]

\end_inset

By trying this solution in 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{2}=\zeta(t^{2})$
\end_inset

 we note that it is actually a general solution for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, the straight line 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1-t$
\end_inset

 is tangent to
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $z^{2}=\zeta(t^{2})$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $(Q,1-Q)$
\end_inset

 for any values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

, as can be checked by substituting in the formula 
\begin_inset Formula $dz/dt=(t/z)(d\zeta/d\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 Note also that 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1-t$
\end_inset

 is the limiting line for the family 
\begin_inset Formula $z=s-s't$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, an obvious parametrization for the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $(s,s')$
\end_inset

 is obtained as follows: 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 i
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s'(t)=-\frac{dz}{dt}=-\frac{t\,\zeta'(t^{2})}{\sqrt{\zeta(t^{2})}},\qquad t_{{\rm min}}\le t\le1-Q,
\]

\end_inset

and next 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 ii
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s(t)=z+ts'(t)=\sqrt{\zeta(t^{2})}+ts'(t),\qquad t_{{\rm min}}\le t\le1-Q.
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\zeta'(\tau)=1-\frac{\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\tau}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $s<z_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 is is always possible to separate the initial states, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $|\Psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 can be made orthogonal.
 We note that the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $s=z_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the unambiguous discrimination result 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q=2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}s,\quad Q=\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}s^{2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next plot is for 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=0.1$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 the curves approach a straight line.
 The difference is more noticeable for very small values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Separation1.graph.pdf
	width 8cm
	height 6cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Experimental realization using optical devices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the interpolation scheme of a general measurement with a Fixed Rate
 of Inconclusive Outcome (FRIO) has been solved by 
\begin_inset Formula $Bagan$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $et$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $al$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bagan2012"

\end_inset

 there has been a quest for a physical realization.
 The authors solved the problem using an operator transformation technique
 that reformulated the intermediate problem into a ME problem with an extra
 optimization parameter.
 Essentially they reduced the problem from a three element POVM to two element
 POVM similar to ME.
 As is the case with POVM solutions, they are not naturally realizable in
 an experimental setting.
 Inspired by the work of 
\begin_inset Formula $Reck$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $et\ al$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reck1994"

\end_inset

 in which they prove that any finite dimensional unitary operator can be
 constructed in the lab using optical devices.
 We set out to solve the intermediate discrimination problem using the Neumark
 setup.
 This gives us a closed form solution as in 
\begin_inset Formula $Bagan$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $et$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $al.$
\end_inset

 In addition it gives a three dimensional unitary operator.
 Using the 
\begin_inset Formula $Reck$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $at$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $al$
\end_inset

 algorithm we express the unitary in terms of beam splitters with corresponding
 coefficients of transmittance and reflectivity.
 Similarly we give a solution to the Minimum error problem and provide the
 necessary beamsplitters with the corresponding coefficients.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Analytical Solution of Interpolation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we solve the intermediate scheme of ME with a Fixed Rate
 of Inconclusive Outcome (FRIO) in two different ways.
 In the first method, through a parametrization, the problem is converted
 into a minimum error whose solution is well known.
 Then there is one last optimization with respect to a 
\begin_inset Formula $FRIO.$
\end_inset

 This method generates the same solution as in 
\begin_inset Formula $Bagan$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $et$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $al$
\end_inset

 in a few lines.
 However to obtain an experimental realization of the interpolation we solve
 it using Neumark's theorem.
 It is a generalized measurement procedure in which the system is embedded
 in a larger Hilbert space with extra degrees of freedom.
 A unitary transformation entangles the system with the extra degree of
 freedom known as ancilla.
 After this interaction has taken place, projective von Neuman measurements
 are carried out on the ancilla.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our input states are qubits, which can be expressed in general as unit length
 vectors in the two dimensional basis spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $|1\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|2\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 In the output of the transformation, we associate the basis state 
\begin_inset Formula $|1\rangle$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $|2\rangle$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle$
\end_inset

 gives no information about the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The unitary transformation should do the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s}|0\rangle_{a} & =\sqrt{p_{1}}|1\rangle\ket 1+\sqrt{r_{1}}|2\rangle\ket 2+\sqrt{q_{1}}|0\rangle\ket 0,\nonumber \\
U|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}|0\rangle_{a} & =\sqrt{r_{2}}|1\rangle\ket 1+\sqrt{p_{2}}|2\rangle\ket 2+\sqrt{q_{2}}|0\rangle\ket 0,\label{eq:frio constraint}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where: 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the probability that state 
\begin_inset Formula $i(i=1,2)$
\end_inset

 is correctly identified, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the probability that the detector mistakenly identifies state 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the failure probability, the detector fails to identify the state at
 all.
 Whenever we get a click in the 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 detector means the results are inconclusive.
 From the unitarity conditions we obtain the normalized probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}+r_{i}+q_{i}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We wish to maximize the probability of success, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}=\eta_{1}p_{1}+\eta_{2}p_{2}$
\end_inset

, and minimize the error rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}$
\end_inset

, for a fixed failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}+P_{e}+Q=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inner product of the two equations in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:frio constraint"

\end_inset

 gives the overlap of the input states in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i},p_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s\equiv\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle=\sqrt{p_{1}r_{2}}+\sqrt{p_{2}r_{1}}+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}.\label{eq:general constraint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is a constraint on the optimization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Optimal solution with equal prior probabilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us first present the solution where the incoming states are given with
 equal a-priori probabilities, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{2}=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies equal error, success and failure rates: 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}=r_{2}$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=p_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=q_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the total error and failure rates reduce to: 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}=r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}=Q.$
\end_inset

 The Neumark set up reduces into
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s}|0\rangle & =\sqrt{p}|1\rangle\ket 1+\sqrt{r}|2\rangle\ket 2+\sqrt{q}|0\rangle\ket 0,\\
U|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}|0\rangle & =\sqrt{r}|1\rangle\ket 1+\sqrt{p}|2\rangle\ket 2+\sqrt{q}|0\rangle\ket 0.
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can immediately solve the constraint equation by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1-r-Q$
\end_inset

, solving the quadratic equation for the error rate in terms of the failure
 rate and overlap 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, which is also the overall failure rate in the IDP limit for the equal
 priors: 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}\equiv2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}s=s$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
s & = & \sqrt{pr}+\sqrt{pr}+Q\nonumber \\
Q_{o} & = & 2\sqrt{r(1-r-Q)}+Q\nonumber \\
(Q_{o}-Q)^{2} & = & 4r(1-r-Q)\nonumber \\
\frac{1}{4}(Q_{o}-Q)^{2} & = & r(1-Q)-r^{2}\nonumber \\
0 & = & r^{2}-(1-Q)r+\frac{1}{4}(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}\label{eq:quadratic IM}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving the quadratic equation and taking the smaller root, 
\begin_inset Formula $i.e$
\end_inset

 the smaller error rate:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r=P_{E}=\frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}],\\
p=P_{S}=\frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)+\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}].
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equal priors case requires no further optimization.
 Simply solving the quadratic equation in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:quadratic IM"

\end_inset

 derived from the constraint the optimal solution is carried out.
 By varying 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 from zero to 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}$
\end_inset

 we recover the Helstrom and IDP bounds.
 In the Helstrom bound one is not allowed to have inconclusive results,
 hence setting failure rate to zero, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0,$
\end_inset

 we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{E} & = & \frac{1}{2}[1-\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}]\nonumber \\
P_{E} & = & \frac{1}{2}[1-\sqrt{1-s^{2}}]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the IDP limit one is not allowed to make an error, 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0,$
\end_inset

 while allowing for inconclusive outcomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
0 & = & \frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}]\nonumber \\
Q & = & Q_{o}\nonumber \\
Q & = & s^{2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Full Solution 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because of the recent interest in this problem, we feel it is beneficial
 to show two new and different approaches to its solution.
 The first is more conceptual: a renormalization inspired by E.
 Bagan et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bagan2012"

\end_inset

 allows us to rewrite the problem as a ME problem with an implicit dependence
 on the last free parameter, the failure rate of one state with relation
 to the other.
 This greatly simplifies the problem as the solution to the first part is
 well known and the second a straight-forward derivative.
 The second solution is a Lagrange multiplier method that is algebraically
 difficult but useful in its explicit results of individual error rate.
 This in turn is useful in designing an implementation scheme.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Transformation of the problem into the Helstrom form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We choose the following transformation to convert our problem into the well
 known Helstrom form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we define the useful quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\equiv s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}$
\end_inset

 which will serve as normalized overlap: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega=\sqrt{p_{1}r_{2}}+\sqrt{p_{2}r_{1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next we normalize all probabilities in the problem: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \tilde{p}_{i}=\frac{p_{i}}{\alpha_{i}},\nonumber \\
 & \tilde{r_{i}}=\frac{r_{i}}{\alpha_{i}},\nonumber \\
 & \tilde{\omega}=\frac{\omega}{\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}},\\
\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}=1-q_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{r}_{i}+\tilde{p}_{i}=1$
\end_inset

, and we have the overlap in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{r_{i}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{p}_{i}:\tilde{\omega}=\sqrt{\tilde{p}_{1}\tilde{r}_{2}}+\sqrt{\tilde{p_{2}}\tilde{r}_{1}}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the above transformation of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 the error rate can be expressed as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{P}_{E}=\tilde{\eta}_{1}\tilde{r}_{1}+\tilde{\eta}_{2}\tilde{r}_{2},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{P}_{E}=\frac{P_{E}}{\eta_{1}\alpha_{1}+\eta_{2}\alpha_{2}}=\frac{P_{E}}{1-Q},\tilde{\eta}_{i}=\frac{\eta_{i}\alpha_{i}}{\eta_{1}\alpha_{1}+\eta_{2}\alpha_{2}}=\frac{\eta_{i}\alpha_{i}}{1-Q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\eta}_{1}+\tilde{\eta}_{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have transformed the problem into a discrimination between two pure states
 with overlap 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\omega}$
\end_inset

 and no explicit failure rate.
 Hence we can simply write down the expression to solution of minimum error
 of two pure states (the Helstrom bound), and then replace the normalized
 quantities with the original expressions: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\tilde{P}_{E} & =\frac{1}{2}[1-\sqrt{1-4\tilde{\eta}_{1}\tilde{\eta}_{2}\tilde{\omega}^{2}}],\nonumber \\
P_{E} & =\frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}}].\label{eq:optimize P_e}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now have one last optimization.
 Given a fixed rate of the average of inconclusive outcomes, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q,$
\end_inset

 what are the individual failure rates 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}.$
\end_inset

 To minimize 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:optimize P_e"

\end_inset

 we maximize the square root term 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}},$
\end_inset

 which in term means to minimize 
\begin_inset Formula $(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}=(s^{2}+q_{1}q_{2}-2s\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}).$
\end_inset

 The overlap term, 
\begin_inset Formula $s,$
\end_inset

 is fixed and we are left with 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}q_{2}-2s\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}.}$
\end_inset

 Only one of the 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}'s$
\end_inset

 is an independent variable as we fix the overall failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Theta & = & q_{1}q_{2}-2s\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}.}\\
\Theta & = & \frac{q_{1}(Q_{0}-\eta_{1}q_{1}^{2})}{\eta_{2}}-2s\sqrt{\frac{q_{1}(Q_{0}-\eta_{1}q_{1}^{2})}{\eta_{2}}}\\
\Theta & = & \frac{\eta_{1}q_{1}Q_{0}-\eta_{1}^{2}q_{1}^{2}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}-2s\sqrt{\frac{\eta_{1}q_{1}Q_{0}-\eta_{1}^{2}q_{1}^{2}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}}\\
\Theta & = & \frac{\tilde{q}_{1}Q_{0}-\tilde{q}_{1}^{2}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}-2s\sqrt{\frac{\tilde{q}_{1}Q_{0}-\tilde{q}_{1}^{2})}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}q_{1}=\tilde{q}.$
\end_inset

 Let's optimize with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{q}_{1}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=\frac{\partial\Theta}{\partial\tilde{q}_{1}}=\frac{Q_{0}-2\tilde{q}_{1}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}-2s\sqrt{\frac{Q_{0}-2\tilde{q}_{1}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
this leads to the optimality condition 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}=2\tilde{q}_{1}=2\eta_{1}q_{1}=2\eta_{2}q_{2},$
\end_inset

 giving us the minimal error rate in discriminating two pure states with
 a fixed rate of failure as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}].
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}=2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}s$
\end_inset

 is the failure rate in the optimal unambiguous state discrimination, which
 our expression reaches when we set 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=0$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand when the failure rate is zero we can recover the Helstrom
 bound for two pure states 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=\frac{1}{2}[1-\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}].$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Lagrange Multipliers Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the above method gives a closed formed solution of the average error
 rate in terms of a FRIO it does not produce individual error or success
 rates, i.e the error rate of mistaking state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 for state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{j}\rangle$
\end_inset

 , which are needed for the implementation in calculating the transmittance
 and reflection coefficients of the beam splitters.
 To obtain these expressions we show another solution to the interpolation
 using the Lagrange multipliers method with constraint in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general constraint"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to minimize the average error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}$
\end_inset

 subject to the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\sqrt{(1-r_{1}-q_{1})r_{2}}+\sqrt{(1-r_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}}+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}},$
\end_inset

 setting up the function with one Lagrange multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda:$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}+\lambda(s-\sqrt{(1-r_{1}-q_{1})r_{2}}-\sqrt{(1-r_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}}-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Setting the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $dF_{(r_{1},r_{2},\lambda)}/dr_{i}$
\end_inset

 to zero then solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}(\lambda)$
\end_inset

, we exploit the symmetry in the resulting equations to solve for the individual
 error rates 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 as a function of the failure rates 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Subsequent substitution into the constraint gives us the optimal value
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can obtain the total minimum error by replacing the expressions
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}$
\end_inset

 and minimizing 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}$
\end_inset

 under the additional constraint that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}=Q$
\end_inset

.
 This gives us the optimal relationship between failure rates as 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}q_{1}=\eta_{2}q_{2}$
\end_inset

 and the total optimal error rate as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Set 
\begin_inset Formula $dF/dr_{1}=0:$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
0 & = & \eta_{1}+\lambda[\frac{(-1/2)(-r_{2})}{\sqrt{(1-q_{1}-r_{1})r_{2}}}-\frac{(1/2)(1-q_{2}-r_{2})}{\sqrt{(1-q_{2}-r_{2})r_{1}}}]\nonumber \\
0 & = & \eta_{1}+(\lambda/2)[\frac{(r_{2})}{\sqrt{(1-q_{1}-r_{1})r_{2}}}-\frac{(1-q_{2}-r_{2})}{\sqrt{(1-q_{2}-r_{2})r_{1}}}\nonumber \\
-(2\eta_{1}/\lambda) & = & \frac{\sqrt{r_{2}}}{\sqrt{(1-q_{1}-r_{1})}}-\frac{\sqrt{(1-q_{2}-r_{2})}}{\sqrt{r_{1}}}\nonumber \\
(2\eta_{1}/\lambda)\sqrt{(1-q_{1}-r_{1})r_{1}} & = & \sqrt{(1-q_{2}-r_{2})(1-q_{1}-r_{1})}-\sqrt{r_{1}r_{2}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $dF/dr_{2}=0$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(2\eta_{2}/\lambda)\sqrt{(1-q_{2}-r_{2})r_{2}}=\sqrt{(1-q_{2}-r_{2})(1-q_{1}-r_{1})}-\sqrt{r_{1}r_{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This step is algebraically challenging and requires the insight that the
 resulting equations can each be separated into two expressions, left hand
 side depending on only 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 and the right hand sides are equivalent.
 Because both equations have the same multivariable expression, we can set
 the left hand sides equal to a constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $C,$
\end_inset

 which is yet to be determined.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(2\eta_{1}/\lambda)\sqrt{(1-q_{1}-r_{1})r_{1}}=(2\eta_{2}/\lambda)\sqrt{(1-q_{2}-r_{2})r_{2}}\equiv C
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This greatly simplifies the problem, turning it into a quadratic equation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(2\eta_{i}/\lambda)\sqrt{(1-q_{i}-r_{i})r_{i}}=C,\label{eq:C}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}\equiv1-q_{i}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{(\alpha_{1}-r_{i})r_{i}}=(\lambda C)/(2\eta_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\alpha_{i}-r_{i})r_{i}=(\lambda^{2}C^{2})/(4\eta_{i}^{2}),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha_{i}r_{i}-r_{i}^{2}-\lambda^{2}C^{2}/4\eta_{i}^{2}=0,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{i}^{2}-\alpha_{i}r_{i}+\lambda^{2}C^{2}/4\eta_{i}^{2}=0,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{i}(\pm)=1/2\left(\alpha_{i}\pm\sqrt{\alpha_{i}^{2}-\frac{\lambda^{2}C^{2}}{\eta_{i}^{2}}}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the error rate which we want to be minimized, thus we take the smaller
 root 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}(-).$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r_{1} & = & 1/2\left(\alpha_{1}-\sqrt{\alpha_{1}^{2}-\frac{\delta}{\eta_{1}^{2}}}\right)=1/2\left(\alpha_{1}-A_{1}\right)\label{eq:r1(lambda)}\\
r_{2} & = & 1/2\left(\alpha_{2}-\sqrt{\alpha_{2}^{2}-\frac{\delta}{\eta_{2}^{2}}}\right)=1/2\left(\alpha_{2}-A_{2}\right)\label{eq:r2(lambda)}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\equiv\lambda^{2}C^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}=\sqrt{\alpha_{i}^{2}-(\frac{\lambda^{2}C^{2}}{\eta_{i}^{2}})}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We replace the expression of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r1(lambda)"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r2(lambda)"

\end_inset

 into the constraint from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general constraint"

\end_inset

.
 First let us rewrite the constraint so it simplifies the algebra later:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}=
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1-r_{1}-q_{1})r_{2}+(1-r_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}+\sqrt{(1-r_{1}-q_{1})(1-r_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}r_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
we use the definition in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:C"

\end_inset

 to reduce the square root term 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{(1-r_{1}-q_{1})(1-r_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}r_{2}}=\frac{\lambda^{2}C^{2}}{4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}=(1-r_{1}-q_{1})r_{2}+(1-r_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}+\frac{\lambda^{2}C^{2}}{4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\equiv(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}$
\end_inset

 and using 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}=1-q_{i},$
\end_inset

 the above expression becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega=(\alpha_{1}-q_{1})r_{2}+(\alpha_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}+\frac{\delta}{4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega=\alpha_{1}r_{2}-\alpha_{2}r_{1}-2r_{1}r_{2}+\delta/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega=\alpha_{1}/2(\alpha_{2}-A_{2})+\alpha_{2}/2(\alpha_{1}-A_{1})-1/2(\alpha_{1}-A_{1})(\alpha_{2}-A_{2})+\delta/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega=\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}-A_{1}A_{2}+\delta/\eta_{1}\eta_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},A_{2}$
\end_inset

 by their respective value
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega=1/2[\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}-\sqrt{\alpha_{1}^{2}-\frac{\delta}{\eta_{1}^{2}}}\sqrt{\alpha_{2}^{2}-\frac{\delta}{\eta_{2}^{2}}}+\delta/\eta_{1}\eta_{2}]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{\alpha_{1}^{2}-\frac{\delta}{\eta_{1}^{2}}}\sqrt{\alpha_{2}^{2}-\frac{\delta}{\eta_{2}^{2}}}=\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}+\delta/\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-2\omega
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Squaring both sides and after some trivial algebra we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{-\alpha_{1}^{2}\delta}{\eta_{2}^{2}}-\frac{-\alpha_{2}^{2}\delta}{\eta_{1}^{2}}-\frac{2\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}\delta}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}+\frac{4\omega\delta}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}=4\omega^{2}-4\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta[\frac{4\omega}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}-(\frac{\alpha_{1}}{\eta_{2}}+\frac{\alpha_{2}}{\eta_{1}})^{2}]=4\omega^{2}-4\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\alpha_{1}}{\eta_{2}}+\frac{\alpha_{2}}{\eta_{1}}=\frac{\alpha_{1}\eta_{1}+\alpha_{2}\eta_{2}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}=\frac{\eta_{1}(1-q_{1})+\eta_{2}(1-q_{2})}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}=\frac{1-Q}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta[\frac{4\omega}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}-\frac{(1-Q)^{2}}{\eta_{1}^{2}\eta_{2}^{2}}]=4\omega^{2}-4\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta[\frac{\omega}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}-\frac{(1-Q)^{2}}{4\eta_{1}^{2}\eta_{2}^{2}}]=\omega^{2}-\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta=\frac{(\omega^{2}-\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2})4\eta_{1}^{2}\eta_{2}^{2}}{4\omega\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-(1-Q)^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now plug 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r1(lambda)"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r_{1} & = & 1/2(\alpha_{1}-\sqrt{\alpha_{1}^{2}-(\frac{\lambda^{2}C^{2}}{\eta_{1}^{2}})})\nonumber \\
r_{1} & = & 1/2(\alpha_{1}-\sqrt{\alpha_{1}^{2}-\frac{1}{\eta_{1}^{2}}\frac{(\omega^{2}-\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2})4\eta_{1}^{2}\eta_{2}^{2}}{4\omega\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-(1-Q)^{2}}}\nonumber \\
r_{1} & = & 1/2(\alpha_{1}-\sqrt{\frac{\alpha_{1}^{2}[4\omega\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-(1-Q)^{2}]-4\eta[\omega^{2}-\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}]}{4\omega\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-(1-Q)^{2}}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The numerator can be greatly simplified
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
 & = & \alpha_{1}^{2}[4\omega\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-(1-Q)^{2}]-4\eta_{2}^{2}[\omega^{2}-\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}]\nonumber \\
 & = & -\alpha_{1}^{2}(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{2}^{2}\omega^{2}+4\omega\eta_{2}\alpha_{1}[\eta_{1}\alpha_{1}+\eta_{2}\alpha_{2}]\nonumber \\
 & = & -\alpha_{1}^{2}(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{2}^{2}\omega^{2}+4\omega\eta_{2}\alpha_{1}(1-Q)\nonumber \\
 & = & -[\alpha_{1}(1-Q)-2\eta_{2}\omega]^{2}\nonumber \\
 & = & -[(1-q_{1})(1-Q)-2\eta_{2}(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}]^{2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 The calculation for 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 goes along the same line.
 Expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 become:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r_{1} & = & \frac{1}{2}[(1-q_{1})-\frac{(1-q_{1})(1-Q)-2\eta_{2}(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}}}]\\
r_{2} & = & \frac{1}{2}[(1-q_{2})-\frac{(1-q_{2})(1-Q)-2\eta_{1}(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally we can substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 into the overall average error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}:$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{E} & = & \frac{1}{2}[1-(\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2})-\frac{(1-Q)(\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}-(\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2})-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}}}]\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)-\frac{(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}}}]\label{eq:P_E(q1,q2)}\\
 &  & \frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}}]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We already show that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:P_E(q1,q2)"

\end_inset

 is optimized for a fixed value of failure rate when 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}q_{1}=\eta_{2}q_{2}.$
\end_inset

 It then reduces into the expression derived above:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{0})^{2}}].
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The individual error and success rates can now be expressed explicitly in
 terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}$
\end_inset

 and most importantly the fixed failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{i} & =\frac{1}{2}[(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}})-\frac{(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}})(1-Q)-\frac{1}{2\eta_{i}}(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}}],\label{eq:r_i}\\
p_{i} & =\frac{1}{2}[(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}})+\frac{(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}})(1-Q)-\frac{1}{2\eta_{i}}(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}}].\label{eq:p_i}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the first time that the individual error and failure rates have
 been calculated.
 It has the advantage that we can now use them in our calculations of the
 beam splitters and phase shifters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Choosing the physical implementation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main reason to seek a solution using the Neumark setup is because it
 lends itself into an optical implementation.
 This implementation, as we will see, can be carried out using only linear
 optical elements (beamsplitters and a mirror).
 The possible states are represented by single photons and a photodetector
 will carry out the measurement process at the output.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To choose the basis we will start with the two mode vacuum state 
\begin_inset Formula $|00\rangle.$
\end_inset

 The total number of photons in both modes is one.
 This two dimensional Hilbert space where our photons live can be spanned
 by the states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|10\rangle,|01\rangle\}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $|10\rangle=a_{1}^{\dagger}|00\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|01\rangle=a_{2}^{\dagger}|00\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 are different modes of the electromagnetic fields.
 The basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|10\rangle,|01\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the basis of qubit in basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|0\rangle,|1\rangle\}.$
\end_inset

 The most general input state can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle=\alpha_{i}|0\rangle+\beta_{i}|1\rangle=\alpha_{i}|10\rangle+\beta_{i}|01\rangle$
\end_inset

 which can be produced by sending a photon into a beam splitter with some
 transmission and reflection coefficient.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To represent a qubit in the six-port we need to add another mode, the vacuum
 mode.
 The six-port corresponds to three input and three output ports.
 Our single photon input state can now be represented as 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle_{in}=\sum_{j=1}^{3}c_{j}a_{j}^{\dagger}|000\rangle$
\end_inset

 and the output states 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}^{\dagger}\rangle=U|\psi_{i}\rangle_{in}=U\sum_{j=1}^{3}c_{j}a_{j}^{\dagger}U^{\dagger}|000\rangle=\sum_{j=1}^{3}\sum_{k=1}^{3}c_{j}M_{jk}^{\dagger}a_{k}^{\dagger}|000\rangle.$
\end_inset

 This is the most general form of the output states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equal a-priors Interpolation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will first show full solution of the equal a-priori case where we use
 the direct sum to set up the Neumark.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For equal priors 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=p_{2}=p,r_{1}=r_{2}=r,q_{1}=q_{2}=Q$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=q$
\end_inset

 will serve as the fixed parameter.
 The two input states to be discriminated can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle_{in}=|1\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle_{in}=\cos\theta|1\rangle+\sin\theta|2\rangle$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|1\rangle & = & \sqrt{p}|1\rangle+\sqrt{r}|2\rangle+\sqrt{q}|3\rangle\label{eq: eq1}\\
U(\cos\theta|1\rangle+\sin\theta|2\rangle) & = & \sqrt{r}|1\rangle+\sqrt{p}|2\rangle+\sqrt{q}|3\rangle\label{eq:eq2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where the error and success rate was calculated in section 4.1.1: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r & = & \frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}]\label{eq:r}\\
p & = & \frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)+\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}]\label{eq:p}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the Neumark setup we can read out six out of nine elements of the unitary
 matrix.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: eq1"

\end_inset

 gives the first column, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eq2"

\end_inset

 gives the second column and the last column can be constructed from the
 conditions of unitarity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get first column, multiply 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: eq1"

\end_inset

 from the left with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra 1,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra 2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra 3:$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\langle1|U|1\rangle=U_{11}=\sqrt{p}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\langle2|U|1\rangle=U_{21}=\sqrt{q}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\langle3|U|1\rangle=U_{31}=\sqrt{r}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get the second column, multiply 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eq2"

\end_inset

 from the left with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra 1,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra 2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra 3:$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\langle1|U|1\rangle+\sin\theta\langle1|U|2\rangle=\cos\theta U_{11}+\sin\theta U_{12}=\sqrt{r}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\langle2|U|1\rangle+\sin\theta\langle2|U|2\rangle=\cos\theta U_{21}+\sin\theta U_{22}=\sqrt{p}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\langle3|U|1\rangle+\sin\theta\langle3|U|2\rangle=\cos\theta U_{31}+\sin\theta U_{32}=\sqrt{q}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the solution of the first column 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i1}$
\end_inset

 ,gives the entries to second column 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\sqrt{p}_{1}+\sin\theta U_{12}=\sqrt{r_{2}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{12}=\frac{\sqrt{r}-\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\sqrt{q_{1}}+\sin\theta U_{22}=\sqrt{p_{2}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{22}=\frac{[\sqrt{p}-\sqrt{r}Q_{o}]}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\sqrt{r_{1}}+\sin\theta U_{32}=\sqrt{q_{2}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{32}=\sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{1+Q_{o}}}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta=Q_{o}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\theta=\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The remaining elements be calculated from the conditions of the unitarity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{T}U=I$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i1}^{2}+U_{i2}^{2}+U_{i3}^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{13}=\pm\sqrt{1-U_{11}^{2}-U_{12}^{2}}=\pm\sqrt{1-p-\frac{r+pQ_{o}^{2}-2\sqrt{pr}Q_{0}}{1-Q_{0}^{2}}}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{Q-Q_{o}^{2}+2\sqrt{pr}Q_{0}}{1-Q_{0}^{2}}}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{Q}{1-Q_{0}}}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where we used:
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{pr}=\frac{1}{2}(Q_{o}-Q),$
\end_inset

 which is derived from the multiplication of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:p"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{23}=\pm\sqrt{1-U_{21}^{2}-U_{22}^{2}}=\pm\sqrt{1-r-\frac{p+rQ_{o}^{2}-2\sqrt{pr}Q_{0}}{1-Q_{0}^{2}}}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{Q}{1-Q_{0}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{33}=\pm\sqrt{1-U_{31}^{2}-U_{32}^{2}}=\pm\sqrt{1-Q-\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{1+Q_{o}}}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{1+Q_{o}-2Q}{1+Q_{o}}}=\pm\frac{\sqrt{p}+\sqrt{r}}{\sqrt{1+Q_{o}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where we used : 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{(1+Q_{o}-2Q)}=\sqrt{p}+\sqrt{r}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The full unitary with the signs of the last column chosen so that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{13}^{2}+U_{23}^{2}+U_{33}^{2}=1.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p} & \frac{\sqrt{r}-\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & -\sqrt{\frac{Q}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{r} & \frac{\sqrt{p}-\sqrt{r}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & -\sqrt{\frac{Q}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{Q} & \sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{1+Q_{o}}} & \frac{\sqrt{p}+\sqrt{r}}{\sqrt{1+Q_{o}}}
\end{pmatrix}\label{eq:U(equal prior)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this presentation the above matrix can be shown that it satisfies all
 the unitary conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The unitary in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:U(equal prior)"

\end_inset

 interpolates between the optimal ME scheme and optimal UD with a fixed
 rate of inconclusive results 
\begin_inset Formula $Q.$
\end_inset

 Setting the failure rate to zero, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0,$
\end_inset

 this collapses it into the unitary of optimal ME:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{ME}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p} & \frac{\sqrt{r}-\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & 0\\
\sqrt{r} & \frac{\sqrt{p}-\sqrt{r}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Which can be simplified further by noticing 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{12})^{2}=(\frac{\sqrt{r}-\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}})^{2}=r,$
\end_inset

 similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{22})^{2}=(\frac{\sqrt{p}-\sqrt{r}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}})^{2}=p$
\end_inset

 simplifying the unitary into: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{ME}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p} & \sqrt{r} & 0\\
\sqrt{r} & -\sqrt{p} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Only one beam splitter in needed for optimal ME measurements.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand setting the error rate of the unitary 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:U(equal prior)"

\end_inset

 to zero gives the optimal UD unitary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{UD}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p} & -\frac{\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & -\sqrt{\frac{Q_{0}}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
0 & \frac{\sqrt{p}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & -\sqrt{\frac{Q_{o}}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{Q_{0}} & \sqrt{\frac{Q_{o}(1-Q_{o})}{1+Q_{o}}} & \sqrt{\frac{1-Q_{o}}{1+Q_{o}}}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All three beamsplitters are still necessary for a general UD measurement.
 This is because the measurement is essentially two-step: in the first step
 we attempt to orthogonalize the states, and upon succeeding we perform
 a projective measurement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now express interpolative unitary in terms of three beamsplitters
 such as 
\begin_inset Formula $U=M_{1}M_{2}M_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 This ordering was derived using the Reck-Zeilinger algorithm which says
 that any Unitary matrix can be expressed in terms of beamsplitters and
 phase shifters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The beamsplitters can be written in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 as it is easy to check the unitarity condition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin^{2}\omega_{i}+\cos^{2}\omega_{i}=1.$
\end_inset

 Then the task is that of calculating 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}=\begin{pmatrix}sin\omega_{1} & cos\omega_{1} & 0\\
cos\omega_{1} & -sin\omega_{1} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}=\begin{pmatrix}sin\omega_{2} & 0 & cos\omega_{2}\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
cos\omega_{2} & 0 & -sin\omega_{2}
\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $M_{3}=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & sin\omega_{3} & cos\omega_{3}\\
0 & cos\omega_{3} & -sin\omega_{3}
\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
U & = & M_{1}M_{2}M_{3}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p} & \frac{\sqrt{r}-\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & \sqrt{\frac{Q}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{r} & \frac{[\sqrt{p}-\sqrt{r}Q_{o}]}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & \sqrt{\frac{Q}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{Q} & \sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{1+Q_{o}}} & \sqrt{\frac{1+Q_{o}-2Q}{1+Q_{o}}}
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & = & \begin{pmatrix}sin\omega_{1}sin\omega_{2} & cos\omega_{1}sin\omega_{3}+sin\omega_{1}cos\omega_{2}cos\omega_{3} & cos\omega_{1}cos\omega_{3}-sin\omega_{1}cos\omega_{2}sin\omega_{3}\\
cos\omega_{1}sin\omega_{2} & -sin\omega_{1}sin\omega_{3}+cos\omega_{1}cos\omega_{2}cos\omega_{3} & -sin\omega_{1}cos\omega_{3}-cos\omega_{1}cos\omega_{2}sin\omega_{3}\\
cos\omega_{2} & -sin\omega_{2}cos\omega_{3} & sin\omega_{2}sin\omega_{3}
\end{pmatrix}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives nine equations and only three independent variables to be calculated.
 We can get all the elements by using just 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{31},U_{32},U_{21}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{2}=U_{31}=\sqrt{Q},sin\omega_{2}=\sqrt{1-r^{2}}=\sqrt{1-Q}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $cos\omega_{3}=-\sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{(1+Q_{o})(1-Q)}},sin\omega_{3}=\sqrt{\frac{1+Q_{o}-2Q}{(1-Q)(1+Q_{o})}}=\frac{\sqrt{p}+\sqrt{r}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)(1+Q_{o})}}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $cos\omega_{1}=\sqrt{\frac{r}{1-Q}},sin\omega_{1}=\sqrt{\frac{p}{1-Q}}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The three beamsplitters with the proper coefficients of reflectivity and
 transmittance are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{\frac{p}{1-Q}} & \sqrt{\frac{r}{1-Q}} & 0\\
\sqrt{\frac{r}{1-Q}} & -\sqrt{\frac{p}{1-Q}} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{1-Q} & 0 & \sqrt{Q}\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
\sqrt{Q} & 0 & -\sqrt{1-Q}
\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $M_{3}=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \sqrt{\frac{1+Q_{o}-2Q}{(1-Q)(1+Q_{o})}} & -\sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{(1+Q_{o})(1-Q)}}\\
0 & -\sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{(1+Q_{o})(1-Q)}} & -\sqrt{\frac{1+Q_{o}-2Q}{(1-Q)(1+Q_{o})}}
\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By choosing the FRIO this matrix minimizes the error rate and maximizes
 the rate of success.
 Hence, by setting the FRIO to zero we obtain the setup to the minimum error
 problem on the other hand setting the error rate to zero gives the setup
 of the optimal unambiguous discrimination where 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset

the optimal inconclusive rate is the 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}=s$
\end_inset

.
 This simplifies the works of the experimentalists because now they only
 need one setup and are not restrained to the extreme points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
General case: Interpolation with general priors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we derive the beamsplitter coefficients necessary to interpolate
 minimum error measurements with a 
\begin_inset Formula $FRIO$
\end_inset

 when the input states are prepared with different a priori probabilities.
 The two input states to be discriminated are 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle_{in}=|1\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle_{in}=\cos\theta|1\rangle+\sin\theta|2\rangle$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
U|1\rangle & =\sqrt{p_{1}}|1\rangle+\sqrt{r_{1}}|2\rangle+\sqrt{q_{1}}|3\rangle\label{eq:U1}\\
U(\cos\theta|1\rangle+\sin\theta|2\rangle) & =\sqrt{r_{2}}|1\rangle+\sqrt{p_{2}}|2\rangle+\sqrt{q_{2}}|3\rangle\label{eq:U2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The error and success rates where calculated in Section 4.1.4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{i} & =\frac{1}{2}[(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}})-\frac{(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}})(1-Q)-\frac{1}{2\eta_{i}}(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}}],\\
p_{i} & =\frac{1}{2}[(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}})+\frac{(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}})(1-Q)-\frac{1}{2\eta_{i}}(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}}].
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From these two equations we can read out six of nine elements of the three
 by three Unitary matrix.
 Multiplying 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:U1"

\end_inset

 on the left hand side by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\langle1|,\bra 2,\bra 3\}$
\end_inset

 will give the elements 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i1},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3.$
\end_inset

 Similarly we can obtain three more elements.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first column is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\langle1|U|1\rangle=U_{11}=\sqrt{p_{1}}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\langle2|U|1\rangle=U_{21}=\sqrt{q_{1}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\langle3|U|1\rangle=U_{31}=\sqrt{r_{1}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second Column:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\langle1|U|1\rangle+\sin\theta\langle1|U|2\rangle=\cos\theta U_{11}+\sin\theta U_{12}=\sqrt{r_{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\langle2|U|1\rangle+\sin\theta\langle2|U|2\rangle=\cos\theta U_{21}+\sin\theta U_{22}=\sqrt{p_{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\langle3|U|1\rangle+\sin\theta\langle3|U|2\rangle=\cos\theta U_{31}+\sin\theta U_{32}=\sqrt{q_{2}}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the solution of the first column 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i1}$
\end_inset

 ,gives the entries to second column 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i2}:$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\sqrt{p}_{1}+\sin\theta U_{12}=\sqrt{r_{2}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{12}=\frac{\sqrt{r_{2}}-\sqrt{p_{1}}\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\sqrt{q_{1}}+\sin\theta U_{22}=\sqrt{p_{2}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{22}=\frac{\sqrt{p_{2}}-\sqrt{r_{1}}\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\sqrt{r_{1}}+\sin\theta U_{32}=\sqrt{q_{2}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{32}=\frac{\sqrt{q_{2}}-\sqrt{q_{1}}\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last column be calculated from the conditions of the unitarity, 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{T}U=I$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i1}^{2}+U_{i2}^{2}+U_{i3}^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{13}=\pm\sqrt{1-U_{11}^{2}-U_{12}^{2}}=\pm\sqrt{1-p_{1}-\frac{r_{2}+p_{1}\cos\theta-2\sqrt{p_{1}r_{2}}\cos\theta}{\sin^{2}\theta}}=\pm\frac{\sqrt{\sin^{2}\theta-p_{1}-r_{2}+2\sqrt{p_{1}r_{2}}\cos\theta}}{\sin\theta}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{23}=\pm\frac{\sqrt{\sin^{2}\theta-r_{1}-p_{2}+2\sqrt{p_{2}r_{1}}\cos\theta}}{\sin\theta}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{33}=\pm\frac{\sqrt{sin^{2}\theta-q_{1}-q_{2}+2\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\cos\theta}}{\sin\theta}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that all the elements have been calculated the Unitary is: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p_{1}} & \frac{\sqrt{r_{2}}-\sqrt{p_{1}}\cos\theta}{\sin\theta} & -\frac{\sqrt{\sin^{2}\theta-p_{1}-r_{2}+2\sqrt{p_{1}r_{2}}\cos\theta}}{\sin\theta}\\
\sqrt{r_{1}} & \frac{\sqrt{p_{2}}-\sqrt{r_{1}}\cos\theta}{\sin\theta} & -\frac{\sqrt{\sin^{2}\theta-r_{1}-p_{2}+2\sqrt{p_{2}r_{1}}\cos\theta}}{\sin\theta}\\
\sqrt{q_{1}} & \frac{\sqrt{q_{2}}-\sqrt{q_{1}}\cos\theta}{\sin\theta} & +\frac{\sqrt{sin^{2}\theta-q_{1}-q_{2}+2\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\cos\theta}}{\sin\theta}
\end{pmatrix}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is worth mentioning that all equations in this section referencing 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 are using the optimal values 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r_i"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:p_i"

\end_inset

 derived in the previous section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we have a full unitary matrix we want to express it in terms of
 linear optical devices.
 Again we use the Reck-Zeilinger algorithm to decompose the unitary in terms
 of beamsplitters.
 The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is decomposed into beamsplitters in the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $U=M_{1}\cdot M_{2}\cdot M_{3}$
\end_inset

, and no phase shifters are needed: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
M_{1} & =\begin{pmatrix}\sin\omega_{1} & \cos\omega_{1} & 0\\
\cos\omega_{1} & -\sin\omega_{1} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix},\\
M_{2} & =\begin{pmatrix}\sin\omega_{2} & 0 & \cos\omega_{2}\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
\cos\omega_{2} & 0 & -\sin\omega_{2}
\end{pmatrix},\\
M_{3} & =\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \sin\omega_{3} & \cos\omega_{3}\\
0 & \cos\omega_{3} & -\sin\omega_{3}
\end{pmatrix},\\
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename BeamSplitters.png
	width 8cm
	height 6cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the coefficients of reflectivity and transmittance are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{R_{i}}=\sin\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{T_{i}}=\cos\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U=M_{1}M_{2}M_{3}$
\end_inset


\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
=
\begin_inset Formula $\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p_{1}} & \frac{\sqrt{r_{2}}-\sqrt{p_{1}}cos\theta}{sin\theta} & \pm\frac{\sqrt{sin^{2}\theta-p_{1}-r_{2}+2\sqrt{p_{1}r_{2}}cos\theta}}{sin^{2}\theta}\\
\sqrt{r_{1}} & \frac{\sqrt{p_{2}}-\sqrt{r_{1}}cos\theta}{sin\theta} & \pm\frac{\sqrt{sin^{2}\theta-r_{1}-p_{2}+2\sqrt{p_{2}r_{1}}cos\theta}}{sin^{2}\theta}\\
\sqrt{q_{1}} & \frac{\sqrt{q_{2}}-\sqrt{q_{1}}cos\theta}{sin\theta} & \pm\frac{\sqrt{sin^{2}\theta-q_{1}-q_{2}+2\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}cos\theta}}{sin^{2}\theta}
\end{pmatrix}=$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\begin{pmatrix}sin\omega_{1}sin\omega_{2} & cos\omega_{1}sin\omega_{3}+sin\omega_{1}cos\omega_{2}cos\omega_{3} & cos\omega_{1}cos\omega_{3}-sin\omega_{1}cos\omega_{2}sin\omega_{3}\\
cos\omega_{1}sin\omega_{2} & -sin\omega_{1}sin\omega_{3}+cos\omega_{1}cos\omega_{2}cos\omega_{3} & -sin\omega_{1}cos\omega_{3}-cos\omega_{1}cos\omega_{2}sin\omega_{3}\\
cos\omega_{2} & -sin\omega_{2}cos\omega_{3} & sin\omega_{2}sin\omega_{3}
\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coefficients of reflectivity and transmittance can be calculated by
 matching the corresponding elements of the unitary and it's decomposition.
 We can get all the elements by using just 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{31},U_{32},U_{21}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{31}=\sqrt{q_{1}}=\cos\omega_{2},\sin\omega_{2}=\sqrt{1-\cos\omega_{2}^{2}}=\sqrt{1-q_{1}}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{32}=\frac{\sqrt{q_{2}}-\sqrt{q_{1}}cos\theta}{sin\theta}=-\sin\omega_{2}\cos\omega_{3}=-\sqrt{1-q_{1}}\cos\omega_{3}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{3}=-\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-q_{1}}}[\frac{\sqrt{q_{2}}-\sqrt{q_{1}}cos\theta}{sin\theta}]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\omega_{3}=\sqrt{1-\cos\omega_{3}}=-\frac{\sqrt{sin^{2}\theta-q_{1}-q_{2}+2\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}cos\theta}}{\sqrt{1-q_{1}}sin\theta}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{21}=\sqrt{r_{1}}=\cos\omega_{1}\sin\omega_{2}=\cos\omega_{1}\sqrt{1-q_{1}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{1}=\sqrt{\frac{r_{1}}{1-q_{1}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\omega_{1}=\sqrt{1-\cos\omega_{1}}=\sqrt{\frac{p_{1}}{1-q_{1}}}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting the coefficients of reflectivity and transmittance the beamsplitter
s are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{\frac{p_{1}}{1-q_{1}}} & \sqrt{\frac{r_{1}}{1-q_{1}}} & 0\\
\sqrt{\frac{r_{1}}{1-q_{1}}} & -\sqrt{\frac{p_{1}}{1-q_{1}}} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix},M_{2}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{1-q_{1}} & 0 & \sqrt{q_{1}}\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
\sqrt{q_{1}} & 0 & -\sqrt{1-q_{1}}
\end{pmatrix},M_{3}=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \frac{\sqrt{sin^{2}\theta-q_{1}-q_{2}+2\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}cos\theta}}{\sqrt{1-q_{1}}sin\theta} & -\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-q_{1}}}[\frac{\sqrt{q_{2}}-\sqrt{q_{1}}cos\theta}{sin\theta}]\\
0 & -\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-q_{1}}}[\frac{\sqrt{q_{2}}-\sqrt{q_{1}}cos\theta}{sin\theta}] & -\frac{\sqrt{sin^{2}\theta-q_{1}-q_{2}+2\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}cos\theta}}{\sqrt{1-q_{1}}sin\theta}
\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All the coefficients can be expressed in terms of the 
\begin_inset Formula $FRIO$
\end_inset

.
 Using the optimal relationship between the individual failure rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}q_{1}=\eta_{2}q_{2}=Q/2$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=Q/2\eta_{1},q_{2}=Q/2\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

 and the above expressions of success and error rates.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{1}=\sqrt{\frac{r_{1}}{1-Q/2\eta_{1}}}$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\omega_{1}=\sqrt{\frac{p_{1}}{1-Q/2\eta_{1}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{2}=\sqrt{Q/2\eta_{1}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\omega_{2}=\sqrt{1-Q/2\eta_{1}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{3}=-\frac{\sqrt{Q/2\eta_{2}}-Q_{o}/2\eta_{1}\sqrt{Q/2\eta_{2}}}{\sqrt{(1-Q/2\eta_{1})(1-Q_{o}^{2}/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2})}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\omega_{3}=\frac{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-Q/(2\eta_{1}\eta_{2})+QQ_{o}/(2\eta_{1}\eta_{2})}}{\sqrt{(1-Q/2\eta_{1})(1-Q_{o}^{2}/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2})}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{\frac{p_{1}}{1-Q/2\eta_{1}}} & \sqrt{\frac{r_{1}}{1-Q/2\eta_{1}}} & 0\\
\sqrt{\frac{r_{1}}{1-Q/2\eta_{1}}} & -\sqrt{\frac{p_{1}}{1-Q/2\eta_{1}}} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{1-Q/2\eta_{1}} & 0 & \sqrt{Q/2\eta_{1}}\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
\sqrt{Q/2\eta_{1}} & 0 & -\sqrt{1-Q/2\eta_{1}}
\end{pmatrix},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{3}=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \frac{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-Q/(2\eta_{1}\eta_{2})+QQ_{o}/(2\eta_{1}\eta_{2})}}{\sqrt{(1-Q/2\eta_{1})(1-Q_{o}^{2}/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2})}} & -\frac{\sqrt{Q/2\eta_{2}}-Q_{o}/2\eta_{1}\sqrt{Q/2\eta_{2}}}{\sqrt{(1-Q/2\eta_{1})(1-Q_{o}^{2}/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2})}}\\
0 & -\frac{\sqrt{Q/2\eta_{2}}-Q_{o}/2\eta_{1}\sqrt{Q/2\eta_{2}}}{\sqrt{(1-Q/2\eta_{1})(1-Q_{o}^{2}/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2})}} & -\frac{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-Q/(2\eta_{1}\eta_{2})+QQ_{o}/(2\eta_{1}\eta_{2})}}{\sqrt{(1-Q/2\eta_{1})(1-Q_{o}^{2}/4\eta_{1}\eta_{2})}}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace 0.05in
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now check the bounds of the general unitary matrix for equal priors
 to see if it reproduces the unitary in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:U(equal prior)"

\end_inset

.
 Indeed, everything checks out and the equal priors unitary matrix is reproduced
: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p} & \frac{\sqrt{r}-\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & \sqrt{\frac{Q}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{r} & \frac{[\sqrt{p}-\sqrt{r}Q_{o}]}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & \sqrt{\frac{Q}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{Q} & \sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{1+Q_{o}}} & -\frac{\sqrt{p}+\sqrt{r}}{\sqrt{1+Q_{o}}}
\end{pmatrix},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Minimum Error
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solution to the minimum error problem was derived in Chapter II.
 Here we use the explicit solution to error and success rates to construct
 the unitary operator which in turn will be expressed in terms of beamsplitters.
 We start with the Neumark setup where a unitary operator entangles the
 input states with the ancilla.
 Let the input states be 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle_{in}=|1\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle_{in}=\cos\theta|1\rangle+\sin\theta|2\rangle$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
U|1\rangle_{in}|0\rangle & =\sqrt{p_{1}}|1\rangle+\sqrt{r_{1}}|2\rangle\\
U(\cos\theta|1\rangle+\sin\theta|2\rangle)|0\rangle & =\sqrt{r_{2}}|1\rangle+\sqrt{p_{2}}|2\rangle
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where the error and success rates were calculated in chapter two:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r_{i} & = & \frac{1}{2}[1-\frac{1-2\eta_{j}s^{2}}{\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}}]\\
p_{i} & = & \frac{1}{2}[1-\frac{1-2\eta_{j}s^{2}}{\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}}]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get the unitary elements multiply on the left by 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle1|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle2|$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First column is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\langle1|U|1\rangle=U_{11}=\sqrt{p_{1}}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\langle2|U|1\rangle=U_{21}=\sqrt{r_{1}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the elements of the first column the second column can be calculated
 and is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\langle1|U|1\rangle+\sin\theta\langle1|U|2\rangle=\cos\theta U_{11}+\sin\theta U_{12}=\cos\theta\sqrt{p_{1}}+\sin\theta U_{12}=\sqrt{r_{2}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{12}=\frac{\sqrt{r_{2}}-\cos\theta\sqrt{p_{1}}}{\sin\theta}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\langle2|U|1\rangle+\sin\theta\langle2|U|2\rangle=\cos\theta U_{21}+\sin\theta U_{22}=\cos\theta\sqrt{r_{1}}+\sin\theta U_{22}=\sqrt{p_{2}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{22}=\frac{\sqrt{p_{2}}-\cos\theta\sqrt{r_{1}}}{\sin\theta}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Unitary matrix is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U=\begin{pmatrix}U_{11} & U_{12}\\
U_{21} & U_{22}
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p_{1}} & \frac{\sqrt{r_{2}}-\cos\theta\sqrt{p_{1}}}{\sin\theta}\\
\sqrt{r_{1}} & \frac{\sqrt{p_{2}}-\sin\theta\sqrt{r_{1}}}{\sin\theta}
\end{pmatrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Only one beam splitter is necessary.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We derived the optimal rate of error for a fixed failure rate when discriminatin
g between two pure states with fixed a-priori probabilities.
 Along the way we found expressions for the individual error rates.
 Then we created an experimental implementation of this procedure using
 the six-rail representation, and found that three beam-splitters are sufficient
 to perform this experiment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter*
Lagrange Multipliers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our works we have relied quite heavily in the Lagrange multipliers when
 optimizing a function which was under the restriction of a constraint.
 We now show why it works.
 The method can be applied to a function of any number of variable but it
 can be more clearly explained in two variables.
 Suppose that we need to find the stationary points of a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y),$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are the two variables, subject to the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x,y)=0.$
\end_inset

 If the constraint is simple then we can solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $y,$
\end_inset

 plug it into the function then solve 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial f/\partial y=0.$
\end_inset

 However for slightly more complicated constraint this can easily lead to
 a very high order equation with cannot be solved analytically.
 In the case of exact cloning, doing just so leads to a sixth order equation
 which is of little use.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To find the stationary points of a function of two variable such as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y),$
\end_inset

 we could just take the total differentia 
\begin_inset Formula $df$
\end_inset

 and set it to zero
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
df=\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}dx+\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}dy=0\label{eq:lagrange 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which leads to two conditions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}=0,\ \ \frac{\partial f}{\partial y}=0\label{eq:lagrange 0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However there is a constraint which means that the differentials 
\begin_inset Formula $dx$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $dy$
\end_inset

 are not independent, they are related to the total differential of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dg=\frac{\partial g}{\partial x}dx+\frac{\partial g}{\partial y}dy=0\label{eq:lagrange 2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiplying 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange 2"

\end_inset

 by the Lagrange parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and adding it to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange 1"

\end_inset

 we get 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d(f+\lambda g)=(\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}+\lambda\frac{\partial g}{\partial x})dx+(\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}+\lambda\frac{\partial g}{\partial y})dy
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation can be satisfied by choosing the Lagrange multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 such that the following two conditions are satisfied:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}+\lambda\frac{\partial g}{\partial x}=0\label{eq:lagrange x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}+\lambda\frac{\partial g}{\partial y}=0\label{eq:lagrange y}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get the stationary points of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)$
\end_inset

 follow this procedure:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Solve the two equations:
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange x"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange y"

\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Plug 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 into the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x,y)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Plug the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Plug 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 into the function which was to be optimized 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we have seen how the Lagrange multipliers method works, we can
 simplify the procedure by optimizing the function following function:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F(x,y)=f(x,y)+\lambda g(x,y)\label{eq:lagrange full}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with respect to the the independent variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y.$
\end_inset

 Differentiating 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange full"

\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y,$
\end_inset

 we obtain equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange x"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange y"

\end_inset

.
 The rest of the procedure is the same.
 This is the exact procedure we used for our works, for example in optimizing
 the error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}(r_{1},r_{2})$
\end_inset

 with one constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $s(r_{1},r_{2}).$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A more general procedure involving a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 variables, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{n}),$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 constrains goes in similar lines.
 We start by setting up 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange full"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F(x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{n})=f(x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{n})+\sum_{\lambda_{j}=1}^{m}\lambda_{j}g_{j}(x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{n}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Optimizing the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{n})$
\end_inset

 we differentiate with respect to all the independent variables 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{n})$
\end_inset

 and follow the procedure defined above.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter*
Reck-Zeilinger Algorithm 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In their letter 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reck1994"

\end_inset

 prove that any discrete finite-dimensional unitary operator can be constructed
 using optical devices only.
 Then they provide a general algorithm which decomposes any 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 unitary matrix into a product of two-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $U(2)$
\end_inset

 transformations which can be expressed as beam splitters, phase shifters
 and mirrors.
 This optical multi-port can act upon various fields such as electrons,
 neutrons, atoms, photons etc.
 The authors decide to work with photons purely for convenience and widespread
 availability of high power lasers.
 It is this very proof which allows us to implement our various works in
 state discrimination and cloning.
 In addition the proof has greatly simplified the experimental realizations
 of many quantum computation, quantum information and quantum cryptography
 schemes.
 Besides these very practical applications it has also answered a long standing
 question: Does an experiment measuring the variables corresponding to any
 arbitrary Hermitian operator exists? They show that indeed an experimental
 realization does exist for an arbitrary operator in a finite dimensional
 Hilbert space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It has long been known that a lossless beam splitter and a phase shifter
 can be implement any 
\begin_inset Formula $U(2)$
\end_inset

 transformation: a beam splitter and a phase shifter at one output port
 transforms the input operators into output operators as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{pmatrix}a'_{1}\\
a'_{2}
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}e^{i\phi}\sin\omega & e^{i\phi}\cos\omega\\
\cos\omega & -\sin\omega
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}a_{1}\\
a_{2}
\end{pmatrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the phase shifter which can be realized as an external phase shifter
 after the beam splitter, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 represents the transmittance and reflectivity coefficient, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{T}=\cos\omega,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{R}=\sin\omega.$
\end_inset

 In their Letter Reck, 
\begin_inset Formula $et$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $al.$
\end_inset

 considered the use of a Mach-Zehner interferometer to simulate the effect
 of a beam splitter which splits the incoming beam according to the given
 parameters of transmittance and reflectivity.
 For an actual two by two beam splitter the coefficients of transmittance
 and reflectivity should be 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{T}=\sin\omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{R}=\sin\theta.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The authors show that starting with an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\times$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 unitary matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $U(N),$
\end_inset

 it can be expressed into a succession of two-dimensional matrices which
 correspond to beam splitters and phase shifters.
 Hence the 
\begin_inset Formula $U(N)$
\end_inset

 unitary matrix can be realized in the full 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 dimensional Hilbert space through a succession of two-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $U(2)$
\end_inset

 matrices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The order in which the matrices are multiplied correspond to the sequence
 in which the beamsplitters are set up.
 The task of realizing the experimental setup of an arbitrary unitary matrix
 becomes that of factorizing the matrix in terms of two dimensional beam
 splitter matrices with phase shifters which can be realized after the beam
 splitters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define an 
\begin_inset Formula $N-$
\end_inset

dimensional identity matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{pq}$
\end_inset

 which multiplies the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 dimensional unitary matrix from the right to reduce the dimensionality
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $N-1.$
\end_inset

 In the identity matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{pq}$
\end_inset

 the elements 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{pq},\;I_{pp},\;I_{qp},\;I_{qq}$
\end_inset

 are replaced by the corresponding beam splitter matrix elements 
\begin_inset Formula $(\cos\omega,\sin\omega)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U(N)\times T_{N,N-1}\times T_{N,N-2}\times...T_{N,1}=\begin{pmatrix}U(N-1) & 0\\
0 & e^{i\phi}
\end{pmatrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This reduces the dimensionality of 
\begin_inset Formula $U(N)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $U(N-1).$
\end_inset

 The process is repeated again until all the off diagonal elements of the
 original unitary matrix are zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U(N)\cdot T_{N,N-1}\cdot T_{N,N-2}\cdot...T_{N,1}\cdot T_{N-1,N-2}\cdot T_{N-2,N-2}\cdot...T_{2,1}\cdot...T_{2,1}=\begin{pmatrix}e^{i\alpha_{1}} & 0 & .. & 0\\
\vdots & e^{i\alpha_{2}}\\
 &  & \ddots\\
0 & \cdots &  & e^{i\alpha N}
\end{pmatrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D=\begin{pmatrix}e^{-i\alpha_{1}} & 0 & .. & 0\\
\vdots & e^{-i\alpha_{2}}\\
 &  & \ddots\\
0 & \cdots &  & e^{-i\alpha N}
\end{pmatrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
we have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U(N)\cdot T_{N,N-1}\cdot T_{N,N-2}\cdot...T_{N,1}\cdot T_{N-1,N-2}\cdot T_{N-2,N-2}\cdot...T_{2,1}\cdot D=I
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The unitary matrix can be expressed in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $Tp,q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D:$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U(N)=D^{-1}\cdot T_{2,1}....\cdot T_{N-2,N-2}^{-1}\cdot T_{N-1,N-2}^{-1}\cdot T_{N,1}^{-1}....\cdot T_{N,N-2}^{-1}\cdot T_{N,N-1}^{-1}\label{eq:reck-seilinger algorithm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Since the product of matrices represents the order of which the beam splitters
 are set up, then 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:reck-seilinger algorithm"

\end_inset

 is all one needs to implements a finite dimensional unitary matrix.
 Since this algorithm is recursive, it can factorize any finite dimensional
 unitary operator.
 For example a 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 unitary matrix, three beam splitters are needed 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{21},T_{31},T_{32},$
\end_inset

 a 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 unitary matrix requires six beamsplitters 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{4,3},T_{4,2},T_{4,1},T_{32},T_{31},T_{21}$
\end_inset

 in reversed order.
 In general the maximum number of beam splitters required for any 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 dimensional unitary operator is 
\begin_inset Formula $\begin{pmatrix}N\\
2
\end{pmatrix}=\frac{N(N-1)}{2}.$
\end_inset

 In practice this method involves a triangular array of beamsplitters, with
 each diagonal row effectively reducing the dimension of the Hilbert space
 by one.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
enter graphics, fig 3 of reck-zeilinger paper.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now give an example to see explicitly how this algorithm works.
 For a three dimensional unitary operator 
\begin_inset Formula $U(3),$
\end_inset

 the algorithm in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:reck-seilinger algorithm"

\end_inset

 gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U(3)=D^{-1}\times T_{2,1}^{-1}\times T_{3,1}^{-1}\times T_{3,2}^{-1}\label{eq:U(3)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-1}=\begin{pmatrix}e^{i\alpha_{1}} & 0 & .. & 0\\
\vdots & e^{i\alpha_{2}}\\
 &  & \ddots\\
0 & \cdots &  & e^{i\alpha N}
\end{pmatrix},\ T_{21}=\begin{pmatrix}\sin\omega_{1} & \cos\omega_{1} & 0\\
\cos\omega_{1} & -\sin\omega_{1} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $T_{31}=\begin{pmatrix}\sin\omega_{2} & 0 & \cos\omega_{2}\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
\cos\omega_{2} & 0 & -\sin\omega_{2}
\end{pmatrix},\thinspace T_{32}=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \sin\omega_{3} & \cos\omega_{3}\\
0 & \cos\omega_{3} & -\sin\omega_{3}
\end{pmatrix}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now plug this 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrices into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:U(3)"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{pmatrix}U_{11} & U_{12} & U_{13}\\
U_{21} & U_{22} & U_{23}\\
U_{31} & U_{32} & U_{33}
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}e^{i\alpha_{1}} & 0 & .. & 0\\
\vdots & e^{i\alpha_{2}}\\
 &  & \ddots\\
0 & \cdots &  & e^{i\alpha N}
\end{pmatrix}\times\begin{pmatrix}sin\omega_{1}sin\omega_{2} & cos\omega_{1}sin\omega_{3}+sin\omega_{1}cos\omega_{2}cos\omega_{3} & cos\omega_{1}cos\omega_{3}-sin\omega_{1}cos\omega_{2}sin\omega_{3}\\
cos\omega_{1}sin\omega_{2} & -sin\omega_{1}sin\omega_{3}+cos\omega_{1}cos\omega_{2}cos\omega_{3} & -sin\omega_{1}cos\omega_{3}-cos\omega_{1}cos\omega_{2}sin\omega_{3}\\
cos\omega_{2} & -sin\omega_{2}cos\omega_{3} & sin\omega_{2}sin\omega_{3}
\end{pmatrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get the elements of the we match the corresponding entries 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ij}$
\end_inset

 with the elements on right hand side.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Enter graphics here from the reck-zeilinger paper for three beam splitters.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig1-coherent.jpg
	width 8cm
	height 6cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter*
Quantum Measurements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the dissertation we used various quantum measurements schemes to read
 out information out of a quantum system.
 For a more thorough understanding of quantum theory of measurements we
 go along the lines of the review paper by J.A Bergou 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bergou2007"

\end_inset

.
 Starting with the standard quantum measurement theory due essentially to
 von Neumann the generalized measurements (Positive Operator Valued Measures,
 POVMs) are introduced as more useful measurements measurement schemes in
 optimization problems.
 Using Neumark's theorem the POVMs can be realized experimentally.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Standard Quantum Measurements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset bibtex
LatexCommand bibtex
bibfiles "/Users/ashehu/Desktop/mendeley"
options "unsrt"

\end_inset


\end_layout

